<HEADLINE> Hillary Calls Attacks on Clinton Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton
Tuesday called the current allegations of sexual misconduct
against U.S. President Bill Clinton part of "a vast right-wing
conspiracy."
</P>
<P>
On NBC television's "Today" show, the first lady said the
attacks on her husband are part of a continuing campaign
undertaken by the political opposition since the day he announced
for president.
</P>
<P>
She said, "Bill and I have been accused of everything including
murder by some of the same people who are behind these
allegations."
</P>
<P>
Asked if it was a "smear," she said "it's a pretty bad one,"
adding, "I don't know what it is about my husband that generates
such hostility."
</P>
<P>
She said there is a "firestorm" of a media "feeding frenzy"
putting out "rumor and innuendo."
</P>
<P>
Hillary accused special counsel Kenneth Starr of being
"politically motivated," trying to dig up "dirt" and questioned
his tactics in using the "justice system for political ends."
</P>
<P>
Starr has expanded a nearly four-year, 30 million-dollar
investigation of the Whitewater land venture to probe allegations
that Clinton had an affair with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
William Ginsburg, the intern's attorney, is negotiating
immunity for Lewinsky who denied in an affidavit having a liaison
with the president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
