<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lucent Innovation Boosts Capacity of Fiber Networks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, January 27 (Xinhua)-- U.S. Lucent Technologies
Incorporated has developed a system that can transmit as many as
400 billion bits of data per second over a single strand of fiber,
a spokesman for the company said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The development is a new achievement of Lucent in its race to
meet the demands of phone companies for a more robust transmission
capacity.
</P>
<P>
The system, which delivers five times the bandwidth of current
systems, raises the standards for systems that use a technology
known as dense wavelength division multiplexing.
</P>
<P>
When configured to work with eight fibers, the system can
transmit as many as 3.2 trillion bits of data a second--the
equivalent of 90,000 encyclopedia volumes in one second, Lucent
said.
</P>
<P>
Lucent plans to begin shipping the product world-wide in the
fourth quarter of this year. That could give competitors time to
develop and deploy their own transmission systems.
</P>
<P>
AT&AMP;T said Monday it plans to deploy Lucent's new system to
double the capacity of its 40,000-mile fiberoptic network by the
end of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
