<HEADLINE> France Says Iraqi Crisis Should be Dealt With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 27 (Xinhua) -- France said on Tuesday that the
on-going crisis in Iraq over U.N. arms inspection should be dealt
with within the United Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"We are very committed to the role and the unity of action of
the Security Council in the solution to the Iraqi problem," said
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves Doutriaux.
</P>
<P>
He also said that diplomatic consultations aimed at reaching a
common stand are going on at the U.N. and in several western
capitals.
</P>
<P>
The United States has indicated that it will act alone in a
military action against Iraq, if Baghdad does not allow U.N. arms
inspectors to carry out their work by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine on Tuesday once again
insisted that France opposes a military attack upon Iraq, and
prefers political or diplomatic ways to solve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
"For the moment, we should continue political and diplomatic
efforts to find a solution. The solution is an Iraqi acceptance to
cooperate with the U.N. Special Commission on disarmament in Iraq
(UNSCOM)," said Vedrine following a meeting with U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan in Paris. 
</P>
</TEXT>
