<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1.1 Million Flood Victims Need Emergency Aid in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP)
said Tuesday that some 1.1 million flood victims in Somalia and
Kenya need emergency assistance and the on-going airdrop
operations should be prolonged until the end of March.
</P>
<P>
WFP appealed Tuesday to international donor community to
pledge additional 12 million U.S. Dollars assistance, saying that
"unless donors provide new funding it will be forced to halt
emergency airlifts and airdrops of food and other vital
supplies."
</P>
<P>
In a news release issued here Tuesday, WFP noted that
additional funding was urgently needed to prolong the emergency
operations because the unusually heavy rains continued until
mid-January in Kenya and much of Somalia.
</P>
<P>
WFP initially predicted that the rain which began in
mid-October would stop in mid-December and conditions would
return to normal by early February.
</P>
<P>
According to WFP, the hardest hit areas in Somalia are Middle
and Lower Juba, Lower Shabelle, Gedo, Bay and Bakool districts
where flooding has severely affected 657,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The floods in Somalia killed 1,980 people and 33,500 heads of
livestock, and destroyed 31,000 tons of food stocks and crops
planted on 60,000 hectares of farmland.
</P>
<P>
In Kenya, food is most urgently needed by 390,000 people in
Tana River, Garissa, Mandera, Isiolo, Wajir and Marsabit
districts in northeastern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
WFP has so far delivered 4,500 tons of food, medicines,
shelter and other supplies to flood victims in the two countries
by airlifts and airdrops starting from mid-November in Somalia
and early December in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. body is also airlifting 500 tons of food a week from
Kenya's port city Mombasa and East Provincial capital Garissa to
125,000 refugees in the Dadaab camps along the border area
between Somalia and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The refugees are totally dependent on the airlift because the
main roads leading to the camps are still impassable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
