<HEADLINE> Clinton, Blair Confer Over Iraq Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
and British Prime Minister Tony Blair agreed in a telephone call
on Tuesday that developments in the standoff over U.N. weapons
inspections in Iraq were "serious."
</P>
<P>
"They share a common determination to see the Security Council
resolutions respected and for the United States and the United
Kingdom to stay closely coordinated on this issue," said a White
House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Reports in the past week said that Britain and the U.S. are
considering an air strike on Iraq if necessary.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will
travel to Europe on Wednesday to coordinate with key foreign
ministers on the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Albright is expected to meet Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov in Madrid, French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine in
Paris and British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook in London.
</P>
<P>
The secretary of state plans to inform her counterparts about a
possible American bombing campaign against Iraq, according to a
United Press International (UPI) report.
</P>
<P>
Details of the trip were still being worked out, said a senior
official who asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
Consultations will deal with "next steps" on Iraq, which has
defied the United Nations by barring its arms inspectors from
certain sites and by refusing to cooperate with an inspection team
led by an American. 
</P>
</TEXT>
