<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Rwanda and Alliance Air in Joint Venture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIGALI, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Rwanda's national airline, Air
Rwanda, has officially merged with Alliance Air, thus creating a
new airline in the region, Alliance Express.
</P>
<P>
An agreement was signed here on Monday by Charles
Ntakirutinka, Rwandan Minister of Transport and Communications,
and John Murray, executive director of Alliance Air, reports
reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Alliance Express will begin operating on
March 1st of this year and will link the capital Kigali to major
cities of the region, notably Entebbe, Nairobi, Kinshasa,
Lubumbashi, Dar-es-Salaam and Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
According to Ntakirutinka, Rwanda takes 51 percent of the
shares in this joint venture, while Alliance Air has provided the
remaining 49 percent.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to be the best and we are not afraid of competing
with other airlines operating in the region," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda, which is aspiring to be integrated into the east
African Community, will greatly benefit from this merger.
</P>
<P>
Alliance Air is owned by South Africa, Uganda, and Tanzania
through their national airlines whose shares are respectively 40
percent for South Africa Airlines and 30 percent for both Uganda
Airlines and Tanzania Airways. 
</P>
</TEXT>
