<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Countries Urged to Focus on Rural </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank President
James Wolfensohn on Tuesday urged African countries to give
priority to rural infrastructure development.
</P>
<P>
African countries should make efforts towards the expansion of
infrastructure in rural areas in order to spur growth in
agriculture, the backbone of African economy, he told officials
from the United Nations Economic Commission for Africa (ECA) and
the Organization of African Unity (OAU) as well as the Ethiopian
government.
</P>
<P>
According to Wolfensohn, human resource development, the
expansion of social services particularly in health and
educational sectors, are imperative for speeding up economic
growth in Africa.
</P>
<P>
He called upon African countries to encourage the involvement
of the private sector through creating viable conditions for
investors and promote good governance as part of endeavors to
overhaul their economies.
</P>
<P>
It is through the integrated efforts of governments,
international and non-governmental organizations as well as the
private sector that sustainable economic prosperity could be a
reality in Africa, he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to recent Kampala summit of heads of state and
government from southern and eastern Africa, he said the summit
discussed strategies, challenges and constraints to economic and
social development in Africa, and called on Africa to establish a
new partnership relations with the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
He also pledged the Bank's support to and cooperation with
Africa in its effort for economic up-swing.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn is on a four-day working visit to Ethiopia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
