<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Backs UN Peacekeeping Proposal for CAfrica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 27 (Xinhua) -- France Tuesday backed a proposal
by the United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan to deploy a
U.N. peacekeeping force in the Central African Republic from
April.
</P>
<P>
"This is exactly what France wants," said French Foreign
Minister Hubert Vedrine after a meeting with the U.N. secretary
general in Paris.
</P>
<P>
Annan proposed Tuesday that U.N. establish a peacekeeping
operation in the Central African Republic from April to take care
of the security and supervise a legislative election scheduled for
August or September this year.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General's recommendation follows a recent
technical mission to the country to assess the U.N.-approved
Inter-African Mission to Monitor the Bangui Agreement (MISAB).
</P>
<P>
MISAB, manned by 750 soldiers from six African countries with
French logistical and financial support, will end its mission by
February 6 after serving in Central African Republic since January
1997.
</P>
<P>
France is also preparing to withdraw its more than 1,400 troops
from Central African Republic by April as part of its military
re-deployment in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Central African Republic, one of the poorest in Africa, was
torn apart by several army mutinies in 1996 and tribal tension
remains high since then.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is not ripe for a total withdrawal of the force.
The idea is to have a U.N. force which can work with the
government during the transitional period for ensuring an open and
balanced election," said Annan.
</P>
<P>
The peacekeeping mission will be composed of 1,400 military
personnel with a limited duration which should be completed in two
or three months after the legislative election, according to the
U.N. chief. 
</P>
</TEXT>
