<HEADLINE> France: International Presence Must be Maintained in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Permanent
Representative of France to the United Nations Tuesday reiterated
his country's position that the international presence must be
maintained to monitor the implementation of the Security Council's
resolutions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Alain Dejammet, who is the current President of the
Security Council, made the comments amidst the current crisis
created by Iraq's refusal to allow members of the United Nations
Special Commission (UNSCOM) to enter certain sites for
inspections.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Dejammet stressed that his country had
always been insistent in its stand on the implementation of the
Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
He said it was in the interest of the international community
to ensure the implementation of resolutions on Iraq's weapons of
mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized the need to maintain a "very strict control" over
the elimination of Iraq's weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The Ambassador said that France had been persistent in its
efforts to convince Iraq to see where its interests lay. 
</P>
</TEXT>
