<HEADLINE> State Employees in Greece Stage Nationwide Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, January 27 (Xinhua) -- State employees in Greece staged
another 24-hour nationwide strike Tuesday in protest against a provision
in the Greek government's new tax bill that allows a change in the
status of workers at loss-making or bankrupt public enterprises and
corporations in the framework of their reform.
</P>
<P>
Trade unions in northern Greece said Tuesday that the participation
rate in the strike ranged between 95 percent for Greek post offices
and the Thessaloniki sewage company and 60 percent for banks, Greek
railways and Greek telecoms organization, the semi-official Athens
News Agency (ANA) reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
All Olympic Airways domestic and international flights at
Thessaloniki's Macedonia airport were cancelled, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Panayiotis Avramopoulos, president of the Thessaloniki Labor
Centre, warned that if the Greek government continued its reform
plans, it would have to deal with the full force of the labor
movement.
</P>
<P>
Greece almost came to a standstill last Thursday as transport
workers held a similar strike which was also taken part in by
employees at post offices, state banks, electricity, telecoms and
water companies.
</P>
<P>
But the Greek government refused to bow to the trade unions'
growing pressure with Prime Minister Costas Simitis saying that the
government would not withdraw the legislation.
</P>
<P>
He said on Monday that state employees must realize that what was
good for the national interest was also good for them because Athens
was seeking a position as an equal partner in the European Union (EU)
and in European Monetary Union (EMU). 
</P>
</TEXT>
