<HEADLINE> UNITA, Angolan Govt Split over Savimbi's Guards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Angola's former rebel movement
UNITA General Artur Vinama left here on Tuesday for UNITA
headquarters in Bailundo to discuss differences between Angolan
government and UNITA over the issue concerning guards of UNITA
Chairman Jonas Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed here to the press by Horacio Junjuvile,
acting head for the UNITA team in the joint committee of the
Angolan peace process.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA leadership will soon make a reply after studying the
government program, Junjuvile said.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that the two sides have agreed on 400 as the
preliminary number for Savimbi's guards, but remain divided on
the time when the number will be finally reduced to 15.
</P>
<P>
The government suggests a term of three to six months while
UNITA wishes for 18 months.
</P>
<P>
Under the Lusaka Peace Accord, the number of Savimbi's guards
will be cut to 15 at the end of the peace process from 150 in the
first phase.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the meeting between Angolan President Eduardo dos
Santos and Savimbi in February, Junjuvile said, the meeting will
be very helpful in promoting the implementation of the peace
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA general arrived here last week to discuss with
Angolan government on the agenda for the next summit between
Savimbi and dos Santos as well as security issues for Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
Local observers believe that the summit will be of major
importance for the end of peace process before February 28.
</P>
</TEXT>
