<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-27 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes Annan's Statement on Missing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus welcomed on Tuesday a
statement by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan on exchange of
information about missing persons between the Greek Cypriot and
Turkish Cypriot sides.
</P>
<P>
Government spokesman Manolis Christofides told his daily press
briefing that the Cypriot government was particularly satisfied
with the Secretary-General's reference welcoming developments
concerning the exchange of information about the location of
graves of missing persons in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Christofides also welcomed Annan's assurance that he would
appoint a U.N. member to a tripartite Committee on Missing
Persons (CMP) as soon as he was informed of the exchange of
information between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Annan's spokesman Fred Eckhard told reporters Monday that the
Secretary-General has been in touch with the International
Committee of the Red Cross concerning the selection of the third
member of the CMP to replace Paul Wurth, who resigned in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The CMP was established in 1981 following an agreement between
the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides, who are represented in the
committee with one member each, along with a representative
appointed by the U.N. Secretary-General.
</P>
<P>
According to the U.N. spokesman, Annan also welcomed a meeting
here last Friday between Greek Cypriot Humanitarian Affairs
Commissioner Takis Christopoulos and Turkish Cypriot
representative Rustem Tatar in the presence of Gustave Feissel,
U.N. resident representative.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Cypriot side handed over information on 200 missing
Turkish Cypriots and the Turkish Cypriot side gave information
about 400 missing Greek Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held under an agreement reached on July 31,
1997 by Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot
leader Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Greek Cypriot-dominated south and
Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey landed
its troops and took over the northern third of the island
following a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,619 Greek Cypriots and Greeks were listed as
missing after the 1974 Turkish invasion. The Turkish Cypriot side
listed some 500 as missing since clashes erupted between the two
sides in 1963 on the island. 
</P>
</TEXT>
