<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Soldiers to Be off Streets, Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean soldiers,
deployed at the height of last week's food riots to stop the
massive destruction of property and looting, will only be
withdrawn after the situation is back to normal, Defence Minister
Moven Mahachi said today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing journalists after signing a defence protocol with
the government of Rwanda, Mahachi said the soldiers will be
withdrawn after Home Affairs Minister Dumiso Dabengwa said there
is now peace and calm in the two areas.
</P>
<P>
He said accusations by the western media that Zimbabwe was
turning its army against its people were unjustified and
sinister.
</P>
<P>
''Those people who were looting were not representing the
whole of Zimbabwe, and if our media endorses such behaviour
saying the government should take a back seat and just look then
that is irresponsible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
''The state would have made a serious mistake if it did not
urgently deploy the army to help the police,'' he said, adding,
''That would have been a serious negligence on the part of the
government because those looters were crooks bent on destabilising
the country.''
</P>
<P>
He said the face that the police were failing to cope with the
riots did not mean that they have failed to deliver their duties.
</P>
<P>
''They did not anticipate such destruction and looting. They
were technically over stretched. In the past 17 years we never
deployed the army to deal with disturbances because there wasn't
such unruly behaviour,'' said Mahachi.
</P>
<P>
The Home Affairs Ministry had to summon help from the army
last week to stop the wanton destruction of property and massive
looting that was taking place in some parts of Harare's high
density areas and the dormitory town of Chitungwiza. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
