<HEADLINE> US Accused of Pursuing Policy Against Iraqi People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has accused the U.S. of
relentlessly practicing a policy of mass annihilation against the
Iraqi people, particularly children.
</P>
<P>
In a statement Tuesday to the Iraqi News Agency, an official
source of the Iraqi Ministry of Commerce said the U.S. was still
obstructing the approval the contracts of foodstuff in the second
phase of the oil-for-food deal.
</P>
<P>
Iraq was allowed to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil
every six months to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian
goods under the oil-for-food deal with the U.N.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi source noted that the amount of milk for January was
not sufficient for distribution among children because it was
about 33 percent below the fixed quota.
</P>
<P>
The source indicated that February would be the second month in
a row that the ration cards would not cover the amount of milk
fixed for children in conformity with the distribution plan.
</P>
<P>
This is due to the delay in the approval of Iraqi contracts
with foreign companies by the U.N. Sanctions Committee which is
dominated by the Americans, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.S. administration was still practicing the
same policy which had already led to the death of more than 1.25
million Iraqis over the past seven years of embargo.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. does not feel such policy sufficient, and is currently
threatening to launch a military aggression against Iraq. But Iraq
is still withholding and is forcefully and firmly challenging the
U.S. hostile policy, he concluded.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under the U.N. sanctions since its 1990 invasion
of Kuwait. The embargo, which barred Iraq from exporting oil, its
economic mainstay, can not be lifted unless U.N. arms inspectors
certify that Iraq has eliminated all its weapons of mass
destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
