<HEADLINE> U.S. State Secretary to Visit Paris Thursday on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The United States Secretary of
state Madeleine Albright will visit Paris on Thursday to discuss
with her French counterpart Hubert Vedrine the Iraqi crisis and
the Mideast peace process, French Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves
Doutriaux said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said Tuesday in Washington that the aim of
Albright's tour to Europe is aimed at convincing European leaders
the need to launch a military attack against Iraq, according to
reports from Washington.
</P>
<P>
France has repeatedly expressed its opposition to a military
action against Iraq, and has insisted that the Iraqi crisis,
caused by Baghdad's confrontation with the United Nations arms
inspectors, must be solved within the United Nations Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
The United States has indicated that it will act alone in a
military operation against Iraq if Baghdad fails to let U.N.
inspectors to carry out their work by the end of this week.
</P>
<P>
France has also expressed its deep worry over the persistent
blockade of the Mideast peace process by Israel, after the effort
by U.S. President Bill Clinton to relaunch the peace process was
disrupted by a sex scandal last week.
</P>
<P>
President Jacques Chirac said Monday that he was deeply worried
about the perspective of a relaunching of the Mideast peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov will
arrive in Paris Tuesday night and will meet with President Chirac
and Foreign Minister Vedrine Wednesday on the Iraqi crisis.
</P>
<P>
Both France and Russia are opposed to a military action against
Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
