<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Row Over Possible Links Between ANC, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Shang Xuqian)
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 27 (Xinhua) -- A row has broken out over
possible links between senior officials of South Africa's ruling
African National Congress (ANC) and crime syndicates reportedly
involved in a string of multi-million cash-in-transit robberies
in the country.
</P>
<P>
The dispute boiled up when a newspaper reported Monday that a
multi-million Rand heist suspect attended the birthday party of
Peter Mokaba, Deputy Minister of Environment and Tourism, two
weeks ago in his Johannesburg home.
</P>
<P>
Colin Chauke, who escaped from Pretoria Central Prison early
last month with five other highly dangerous men in detention, was
allegedly seen at the 40th birthday party of Mokaba on January 10
by a police informant.
</P>
<P>
Mokaba quickly denied any knowledge of the presence of the
escapee at his birthday party. But opposition parties demanded an
immediate suspension of Mokaba and a full investigation into the
issue.
</P>
<P>
Mokaba, a member of the all-powerful decision-making National
Executive Committee of the ANC, is an active politician
advocating the divorce of the ANC and its alliance, the South
African Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
Mokaba said he had never known or met Chauke and would not
have known if the fugitive had been at the party.
</P>
<P>
There were hundreds of people at the informal party, many of
whom he did not know, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Chauke was arrested in connection with a 12.6-million-Rand
(2.6-million-Dollar) robbery at a cash depot of the joint bank
security company, SBV, in Pretoria last October. He was believed
to belong to a crime syndicate which possibly designed several
military-style cash-in-transit ambushes.
</P>
<P>
He was a former cadre of Umkhonto we Sizwe (spear of the
nation), the now-defunct military wing of the ANC, also known as
MK. He was also a former ANC local government councilor.
</P>
<P>
The indications of possible links between ANC officials and
criminal MK members sparked a wave of harsh criticism from the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
Several opposition parties have demanded that the ANC
government should immediately dissociate itself from "friends"
and former Mks involved in criminal activities and act to halt
crime.
</P>
<P>
The National Party (NP), the biggest opposition in the
country, said the ANC owed the country an explanation about the
relationship between criminal MKs and present ANC members.
</P>
<P>
NP spokesman Daryl Swanepoel said the Mokaba party attended by
an escaped robbery suspect was but "the umpteenth example of ANC
links with former MK cadres."
</P>
<P>
"The NP reiterates its call for an independent investigation
into the involvement of MK in crime," he said.
</P>
<P>
Swanepoel said questions needing answers included whether the
ANC derived funds from crime to finance its election campaign,
and if so, were President Mandela or other ANC top leaders aware
of this.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Party (DP) and the Freedom Front (FF), both
white-based opposition parties, also called for a thorough
investigation into the matter.
</P>
<P>
DP leader Tony Leon said it was "shocking" that ANC members in
positions of public trust, and who handled public money, should
consort with thieves and hijackers.
</P>
<P>
"This is a shocking confirmation of this government's
inability and unwillingness to deal with crime," he said.
</P>
<P>
He called on President Mandela to suspend Mokaba instantly,
pending a full investigation of his relationship with Chauke.
</P>
<P>
However, the ANC said Mokaba was not accountable for the
presence of the suspect in his house.
</P>
<P>
To make the matter more complicated, Chauke was one of the
three suspected armed robbers, all former MK members, who were
reportedly visited by Safety and Security Minister Sydney
Mufamadi in prison.
</P>
<P>
A lawyer acting for one of the three at the time threatened to
seek an urgent interdict against Mufamadi, who, he claimed,
interviewed his client for more than an hour.
</P>
<P>
Mufamadi denied interviewing the suspects, but admitted
speaking to them during a prison visit to examine the jail
condition.
</P>
<P>
Chauke and the five other prisoners, all suspected members of
various syndicates behind a number of brutal cash robberies,
staged a daylight breakout on December 5 with a firearm smuggled
into the prison.
</P>
<P>
Late last year, ANC Women's League President Winnie
Madikizela-Mandela alleged that Mufamadi personally knew some of
the MK members involved in heists, but had failed to take action
against them. Mufamadi denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
Mufamadi Saturday threatened to be tough on former MKs who
should take part in violent crimes. He said the government would
have no mercy whatsoever.
</P>
<P>
The government had "no sentimental attachment" to former MK
cadres who were using their military training to steal and kill,
he said.
</P>
<P>
According to a special team, which began an investigation into
over a dozen military-style robberies since 1995, at least four
former MK members have been arrested in connection with
well-planned highway ambushes over the Christmas and New Year
period, in which several security guards were shot dead and
millions of Rand stolen.
</P>
<P>
Military specialists said the training former MK cadres
received made investigations extremely difficult.
</P>
<P>
Another factor complicating the problem is corrupt elements in
the criminal justice system. Dockets go missing, prisoners are
sprung from jail and car thieves are given blank car registration
forms by those in a position to do so, said Bushie Engelbrecht,
head of a special team to investigate military-style heists.
</P>
<P>
Critics complained that in spite of increasing indications
that police know who is behind the heists, the gangs are picking
their targets at will.
</P>
<P>
Mufamadi had to admit that "the government has an obligation
to be inward looking. Some of the syndicates are pulling off
their operations because of a connection with state
institutions."  
</P>
</TEXT>
