<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government and
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) mission reached here today
an agreement on major policy elements of the economic program to
be implemented by Zimbabwe in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The IMF mission is in Harare to discuss an economic program that
will be supported by a one-year IMF stand-by credit of three
billion Zimbabwean Dollars (about 180 million U.S.Dollars).
</P>
<P>
''The discussions went well and understnadings were reached on
most of the major policy elements of the economic program for
1998," the IMF said.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government has to promise the IMF that it will
implement its land reform program in accordance with the
constitution of Zimbabwe and consistent with its limited
financial capacity, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The resettlement program will be done in a transparent manner
and its pace and implementation in accordance with the fiscal
framework agreed with the imf mission.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean government has also assured that the program
will safeguard agricultural productivity and the welfare of farm
workers.
</P>
<P>
''The Zimbabwean government has also advised the mission that
it is committed to full consultation with the farming
community,'' the IMF said. 
