<HEADLINE> Chinese Celebrate Lunar New Year (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Local resident in Hefei, the capital of east China's Anhui
Province, flocked to the city's major shopping centers to shop,
guess lantern riddles, a traditional festival game in China. Shops
in Hefei were reportedly decorated with more than 10,000 lanterns
and offered a total of 100,000 festival riddles.
</P>
<P>
Sanya, China's southernmost city in the island province of
Hainan, greeted nearly 200,000 tourists on the first day of the
Spring Festival.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Chinese citizens, especially those living in
the north, have opted to spend their winter holidays in
Hainan. The island's average winter temperature of over 20 Celsius
degrees promotes the growth of roses and orchids.
</P>
<P>
People in Xi'an and Lanzhou, the respective capitals of
northwest China's Shaanxi and Gansu provinces, ushered in the year
of tiger with a series of grand lantern festivals, exhibitions and
performances.
</P>
<P>
Members of more than 50 professional and amateur art troupes in
northwest China's Qinghai Province sacrificed their chance for
family reunions to perform for farmers and herdsmen in vast rural
and pastoral areas.
</P>
<P>
The Qinghai provincial government sent over 1.4 million
kilograms of food, 600,000 pieces of clothing and quilts, medical
products valued at over 400,000 yuan (50,000 US dollars), and
relief funds totalling several million yuan to southern areas in
the midst of a serious snow disaster which began last September.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that members of some ethnic minorities do not
regard the Spring Festival as the start of a New Year, the day was
nonetheless a grand occasion for celebration.
</P>
<P>
Residents in Lhasa, capital of southwest China's Tibet
Autonomous Region, awoke early and dressed themselves in their
holiday best. The residents of Lhasa gathered in the large square
below the well-known Potala Palace to enjoyed song and dance
performances, modern drama and traditional Tibetan opera.
</P>
<P>
According to Toinzhub Cering, a Tibetan singer who sang "Lovely
Motherland, "I wanted to express my sincere love for
the motherland."
</P>
<P>
A jubilant atmosphere permeated Yinchuan, the capital of the
northwestern Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, today as both the
Muslim and Han people wore their festival best and exchanged
greetings on the streets.
</P>
<P>
This year's Bairam Festival, one of three major Muslim
festivals, will be celebrated in two days according to the Islamic
calendar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
