<HEADLINE> Iraq Paper Slams Butler for Breaching Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, January 28 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi daily has slammed
chief U.N. arms inspector Richard Butler for breaching rules of
his work in his capacity as an international envoy representing
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Al-Jumhuria (The Republic) newspaper said Wednesday that
Butler, chairman of the U.N. Special Commission in charge of
eliminating Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, told mass media
that Iraq possesses biological weapons enough to annihilate the
population of Tel Aviv, capital of Israel.
</P>
<P>
The paper pointed out that at the peak of America's
preparation to launch military actions against Iraq, Butler made
this kind of accusation in order to thwart the Russian special
envoy's mission in Baghdad and to give America additional pretext
to launch its aggression.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin's special envoy Victor
Posuvalyuk is now in Baghdad to seek a peaceful solution to the
crisis triggered by the Iraqi proposal to freeze discussions or
actions regarding UN arms inspectors' access to presidential sites
during Butler's visit to Baghdad a week ago.
</P>
<P>
The daily stressed that Butler should not release statements
concerning a subject still under discussion and should not "poke
his nose in political dispute" between two states.
</P>
<P>
It went on to say that Butler's duty is to present information,
if he has, to the Security Council, not to publish it through mass
media. 
</P>
</TEXT>
