<HEADLINE> Snow Storm Sweeps Three Eastern U.S. States </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 28 (Xinhua) -- A state of emergency was
posted for all 100 counties in North Carolina because of a fierce
winter storm that dropped up to two feet of snow in the mountains
in the state and in Virginia and Tennessee on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Highways were shut and schools were closed Tuesday, while power
outages left 62,000 homes in the dark and cold Tuesday night. Two
motorists died in separate weather-related accidents in North
Carolina, local media reports said.
</P>
<P>
A gale warning was posted Wednesday for North Carolina's
coastal waters. Wind gusts of 45 mph and seas of 12 feet were
possible. A coastal flood warning was posted from Ocracoke Inlet
north to the Virginia line.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, a new storm knocked out electrical service for
75,000 of customers in Maine because of a storm that piled snow up
to 10 inches deep and glazed it with ice. Dozens of people were
killed in the storm.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, an ice-storm blacked out hundreds of
thousands of people across the Northeast and Quebec. By Friday,
about 1,000 business and residential customers were still without
power. 
</P>
