<HEADLINE> Chinese Celebrate Lunar New Year (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Cities and villages throughout
China are revelling in a pleasant and harmonious atmosphere in
celebration of the Lunar Spring Festival.
</P>
<P>
Chinese people from various ethnic groups are united around the
Central Committee of the Communist Party of China, with General
Secretary Jiang Zemin at the core, and are striving to record new
achievements in socialist material, as well as ethical and
cultural progress in the year of tiger.
</P>
<P>
At the stroke of midnight on New Year's Eve, Beijing residents
traditionally listen to the 108 tolls of a giant 500-year-old bell
housed in the Big Bell Temple on the capital's Third Ring Road.
The bell tolls 108 times.
</P>
<P>
Loudspeakers strategically placed throughout the city echo the
tolls of the bell to traditionally ring in the New Year.
</P>
<P>
Temple fairs held in the city's major parks and temples have
been drawing throngs of Beijing citizens to watch acrobatic
performances and enjoy traditional food.
</P>
<P>
Many Shanghai residents celebrate the first day of the Lunar
New Year by visiting libraries and bookstores, with the Shanghai
Library attracting as many as 2,000 visitors, mostly youngsters,
on holidays.
</P>
<P>
Wu Tingting, a first year middle school student visiting a
downtown book market, said she was buying books with the money she
received as a New Year's gift.
</P>
<P>
Health food shops and health care centers are also popular
venues during Spring Festival. Local residents are exhibiting
greater concern for their health, and rising income levels have
enabled a growing number to visit restaurants or travel during the
festival period.
</P>
</TEXT>
