<HEADLINE> Chinese Celebrate Lunar New Year (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
People relocated as a result of the Yangtze River Dam Project
are celebrating Spring Festival in their new homes in Chongqing,
China's newest municipality.
</P>
<P>
Zou Houlun, a relocated farmer living Chongqing's Wushan County,
said he will work hard over the next three years to greatly
improve his livelihood.
</P>
<P>
Residents in Nanjing, capital of east China's Jiangsu Province,
traditionally visit the lantern festival held in the Confucius
Temple.
</P>
<P>
Sending fresh flowers to extend New Year's greeting has become
the vogue in Hangzhou, capital of eastern Zhejiang province.
</P>
<P>
Continuing light rain over the past few days failed to put a
damper on the high spirits of people in the south China city of
Guangzhou, with the first day of Spring Festival traditionally
dedicated to family reunions, shopping trips or visits to flower
shows.
</P>
<P>
Florists in the eastern coastal city of Fuzhou had a busy day
filling orders for numerous customers.
</P>
<P>
