<HEADLINE> Divergence of Views Leads to Sri Lankan Minister's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Deputy Defense
Minister Anuruddha Ratwatte decided to resign from his post
because he disagrees with President Chandrika Kumaratunga on the
government's plan of the 50th independence day celebrations, a
reliable military source disclosed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ratwatte, who is also minister of irrigation and power,
submitted a two-page resignation letter to the president Wednesday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister said in the letter that he decided to
resign because he felt responsible for a massive bomb attack by
the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) in Kandy Sunday
morning.
</P>
<P>
However, the source said that the real reason was that he
disagrees with the president on canceling the main celebrations
scheduled to be held in Kandy, the ancient capital of Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The government announced Wednesday morning that the Golden
Jubilee celebrations of independence, which falls on February 4,
will be shifted from Kandy to Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Ratwatte said the move would only satisfy the LTTE, which by
bombing Kandy city has humiliated the government and marred the
celebrations. Thus he insisted the government should stick to the
original plan.
</P>
<P>
However, Kumaratunga rejected Ratwatte's proposals and decided
to hold the celebrations in Colombo.
</P>
<P>
Both the president and the deputy minister deliberately hid
their divergence of opinion to the public, the source said, adding
that Ratwatte's real motive to resign is an open secret among the
military circle. The president holds the post of defense
minister.
</P>
<P>
A truck bomb detonated by LTTE rebels killed 16 people and
damaged the holiest Buddhist shrine, the Dalada Maligawa (Tooth
Relic Temple), arousing the nation-wide anger against the
organization and serious criticism on security lapse.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition, the United National Party, on learning
Ratwatte's resignation decision, has further requested him to quit
his portfolio in the Irrigation and Power Ministry too.
</P>
<P>
It's not clear whether the president has accepted the
resignation or not.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
