<HEADLINE> Zambia Denies Reports of UNITA Bases in Its </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Zambia on Wendesday denied
categorically a report that the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) has military bases in its
territory.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Keli Walubita said his country is irrevocably
committed to peace in the neighboring country and assiduously
works for the full implementation of the Lusaka Peace Accord
signed by the Angolan government and the UNITA in 1994 under the
auspices of Zambia.
</P>
<P>
Voice of America reported on Tuesday that Zambia has UNITA
bases and that Zambezi town in north western province is being
developed as a major supply base for the former anti-government
forces and now an opposition party of Angola.
</P>
<P>
The minister said these baseless allegations are being
perpetrated by those who, for their own selfish motives, are bent
on destroying "the warm, cordial and friendly relations" between
Zambia and Angola.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's commitment to the Angolan peace process was
exemplified by its support for the U.N. sanctions against the
UNITA as well as a quick and decisive action against a South
African airline company which abused Zambian territory on a
number of occasions last year to fly into UNITA-controlled
territory.
</P>
<P>
Walubita said Zambia did not and will not allow its territory
to be used for hostile activities against any neighboring
country. 
</P>
