<HEADLINE> Hainan Witnesses Revival in Its Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, January 28 (Xinhua) -- The economy of the island
province of Hainan, China's largest special economic zone,
continues to recover from a 1995 economic slump triggered mainly
by sluggish real estate development.
</P>
<P>
The province's Gross Domestic Product (GDP) grew by 6.7 percent
in 1997. Its annual growth rate of GDP is expected to stand at an
average eight percent over the next three years, experts said.
</P>
<P>
Hainan in 1996 shifted its development priorities to agriculture,
industry, tourism, and various other pillar industries. As a
result, the proportion of investments in capital construction in
agriculture grew from 3.9 percent to 5.2 percent, while the
percentage for the manufacturing sector rose from 19.2 percent to
23.8 percent and that for tourism jumped from 11 percent to 17
percent.
</P>
<P>
During the 1995-97 period, the province's vegetable output rose
from 1.63 million tons to 2.11 million tons, fruit output from
360,000 tons to 390,000 tons, and aquatic products output from
430,000 tons to 520,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Thirty enterprises were reorganized through bankruptcy or
merger, thus making better use of 660 million yuan in capital
assets, offseting debts of 803 million yuan, and increasing
investments in enterprises by 347 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The island, a major tourism attraction, hosted 5.5 million
tourists in 1997, 1.89 million more than the figure for
1995.  
</P>
</TEXT>
