<HEADLINE> Pakistan Customs Detects 445 Narcotics Cases in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's customs detected
445 narcotics cases in the year of 1997 and 190 people were
arrested in these cases in the country.
</P>
<P>
The cases involved 499.159 kilograms of heroin, 39,486.76
kilograms of charas, 261.1 kilograms of opium and 4,642 kilograms
of acetic anhydride, according to a report compiled by the
Intelligence and Investigation Department of the Customs.
</P>
<P>
The report said that smuggling of heroin out of Pakistan
through airports was the dominant feature in the 445 cases, out of
which 116 cases involved heroin smuggling by outgoing passengers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, smuggling of heroin through postal units was also on
rise in the country, said the report, adding that 259 cases
involving 57.738 kilograms of heroin were detected in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In addition, nine cases involving 199.68 kilograms of heroin
were detected inland during the year, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
