<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Budgetary Deficit Crosses IMF Limit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's budgetary deficit
in the first half of 1997-98 fiscal year has reached 6.3 percent
of the gross domestic product (GDP) against the whole year target
of 5 percent fixed by the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of the fiscal year starting from July
1, 1997, the Pakistani government has borrowed 170 billion rupees
(3.86 billion U.S. dollars) from banks, non-bank and external
sources, official sources said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The budgeted overall borrowing for the whole year, however, is
only 200 billion rupees (4.54 billion dollars), the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The heavy borrowing was mainly because of the disappointing
situation of revenue collection in the first six months, said the
sources.
</P>
<P>
During the period, the government collected tax revenue of 135
billion rupees (3.07 billion dollars), showing 27 billion rupees
(614 million dollars) short of the target.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in the absence of any downsizing of the government,
slow privatization and failure of schemes for the recovery of bank
defaults, the current expenditure has shot out of the budgeted
limits, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
If the shortfall in revenue collection expands further in the
coming months and less than budgeted resources flow in from
privatization and bad debt recovery schemes, the sources said that
the budgetary gap is expected to expand further to over 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Pakistan's GDP growth rate, which was fixed at 6
percent in the budget, has been revised downwards recently by the
government.
</P>
<P>
While explaining the revision, Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz
said that the country would only be able to achieve a growth rate
of 5.2 percent because of slow-down in the large scale industrial
sector and the damage sustained by cotton crop due to heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that a 5.2 percent growth is expected to take
the GDP to around 2.7 trillion rupees (61.4 billion dollars) from
last fiscal year's 2.56 trillion rupees (58.18 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Against this anticipated GDP of 61.4 billion dollars for the
whole year, the government had so far already borrowed 3.86
billion dollars in the first six months, which is 6.3 percent of
the GDP, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund has agreed to provide a loan of
1.6 billion dollars to Pakistan under a three-year structural
adjustment agreement, under which the budgetary deficit for the
whole year was fixed at 5 percent of the GDP.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980128.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-28 </DATE_TIME>
