<HEADLINE> India Bans on Sale of Non-Iodized Salt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, January 28 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government
Wednesday imposed a nationwide ban on sale, possession or
consumption of non-iodized salt.
</P>
<P>
An official notification issued here prohibits any person from
selling or offering or keeping in his premises common salt for
direct human consumption unless it is iodized.
</P>
<P>
The act also makes it mandatory to label the containers/
package as to whether it contains permitted anti-caking agent.
</P>
<P>
In India, iodine deficiency has affected 60 million people who
are suffering from endemic goiter and nearly 8.8 million people
with mental or motor disorders.
</P>
<P>
India took a policy decision to iodize the entire salt in the
country in 1992. With the issuing of present official
notification, it is proposed to bring down the incidence of iodine
deficiency disorders below ten percent level by 2000, the
notification said.
</P>
<P>
Under the official notification, common salt may be sold for
iodization, iron fortification, animal fats preservation,
manufacturing, medicines and industrial use under proper label
declarations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980128.0065 </DOCNO>
