<HEADLINE> Feature: Parade, Fiesta Start off Tiger Year in HK (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of thousands of
local citizens and foreign visitors poured into the streets
Wednesday to admire the Lunar New Year Parade and Fiesta, a
festive celebration to start off the Year of the Tiger.
</P>
<P>
At an opening ceremony of the party in the afternoon,
Administrative Secretary of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR) Anson Chan said that she was delighted to have this
opportunity to wish all the Hong Kongers "a very happy and
prosperous Chinese New Year."
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong had faced many challenges in the past and each time
we overcame these challenges and emerged stronger and more
resilient. Our economic fundamentals remain very strong," Chan
said, stating that she is confident that "with the concerted
efforts of the (SAR) government and the community, Hong Kong will
continue to prosper in the years ahead."
</P>
<P>
She repeated that she "wishes all a very, very happy year of
the Tiger."
</P>
<P>
The parade army composing of over 15 colorful floats and some
40 performance teams started at 14:00 local time (GMT 06:00) in
Kowloon, Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The spectacular pageantry that led the parade symbolized the
numbers "1," "9" and "98" -- one column of red and gold flags;
nine dragons representing longevity and good fortune; and 98 lions
representing the spirit and vitality of Hong Kong and its people.
</P>
<P>
The parade took a 1.35-kilometer route along Salisbury Road,
Chatham Road South and Mody Road to the Urban Council Centenary
Garden, Tsim Sha Tsui East, where its arrival heralded the opening
of the fiesta.
</P>
</TEXT>
