<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Stronger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 28 (Xinhua) -- A recovery in banking stocks
and a surge by gold companies spurred the Australian share market
higher Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index closed 17.2 points higher at 2,621.1,
with the overnight rise on Wall Street and a firmer Japanese
market also helping the buying sentiment.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index closed 21.9 points higher at 4,485.3
with the banking index improving almost one percent.
</P>
<P>
National Australia Bank led the recovery of banks from
Tuesday's big falls with a 48 cent rise to 20.25 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Westpac bank improved 11 cents to 9.83 Australian dollars and
ANZ added four cents to 9.42 Australian dollars while Commonwealth
was the only major bank to post a fall, losing 8.3 cents to 18.21
Australian dollars despite being the strongest in the recent
losses.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index added 14.7 points to 1,135.2, with much
of the strength coming from the Australian gold sector.
</P>
<P>
The gold index jumped 64 points to 1,126.0.
</P>
<P>
Rio Tinto shares dropped 22.5 cents to 19.26 Australian dollars
on reports of reduced profit forecasts from a leading global
brooking house which caused a drop in the London-listed shares.
</P>
<P>
BHP shares improved 23 cents to 14.10 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 321.22 million shares worth 578.51
million US dollars with rises outnumbering falls 615 to 522.
</P>
