<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
said here Wednesday that peace talks between the government and
the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) will continue next month
despite fresh outbreak of hostilities in Maguindanao, Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Ramos told a press conference that both sides have made
commitments to hold the peace talks as scheduled from February 4
to 6.
</P>
<P>
On the part of the MILF, the commitment was made by MILF deputy
chief Ghazali Jaafar, he said.
</P>
<P>
Renewed fighting erupted early this week after the MILF
attacked a government army outpost and Consunji Timber Co. in
Buldon, Maguindanao. The government force retaliated by pounding
the main camp of the MILF with 105mm howitzers.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said the fighting will not affect the resumption of peace
negotiations in the Southern Marawi city next month.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said that he ordered Jesus Dureza, the newly named
presidential assistant for Mindanao, to go to Buldon Wednesday "to
bring about an improvement in the peace and order condition."
</P>
<P>
Both sides are working "for the purpose of improving the
atmosphere for the resumption of their negotiations in accordance
with the agreement on the general cessation of hostilities"
reached last July.  
</P>
