<HEADLINE> Microsoft's Need to Innovate Defended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Bill Gates, chairman of the
U.S. software giant Microsoft Corp. Tuesday asserted his company's
need to innovate free from government interference.
</P>
<P>
Gates expressed the idea while talking with Californian
reporters on the ongoing antitrust case brought about by the
U.S. Department of Justice against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
Last month, a federal judge ordered Microsoft to stop requiring
computer makers to get its Internet Explorer Web browser software
when they buy its Windows 95 operating system, pending a final
court decision.
</P>
<P>
But Gates insisted that his company has nothing to apologize
for, saying that the antitrust case had not damaged his company's
reputation. He said his company should innovate and put new
features in the operating system.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters that the reason his company doubled R &AMP; D in
the past three years is that it wants to maintain its position in
the market.
</P>
<P>
"We know unless we do that we will be replaced," he said. "All
the factors that drive the popularity are available to anybody out
there in the marketplace and there are many other operating
systems out there competing."
</P>
<P>
At Stanford, Gates criticized some Justice Department officials
for lacking even a basic understanding of technical issues.
</P>
<P>
Some recent polls had indicated that Americans have a generally
favorable impression of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
But those polls also revealed a broadly negative reaction to
Microsoft's aggressive stance in its court battle with the Justice
Department, a stance that almost brought the company to a contempt
of court citation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
