<HEADLINE> Green-House Peony Adds Rich Scent to Freezing East China Village </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Looking at thousands of blooming
peony in his greenhouse, Zhao Xiaodong, a floral planter in Heze
County of east China's Shandong Province, said proudly: "They are
my money trees."
</P>
<P>
Indeed, each sapling of Zhao's peony is worth 300-to-400 yuan
(36-48 U.S. dollars) and each of his peony buds is worth 50-to-60
yuan. The Spring Festival of China's Lunar New Year drew orders of
1,200 peonies cultivated in his two greenhouses, worth 300,000
yuan (36,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The floral industry has a long history in Heze County, titled
"Hometown of Chinese Peony" by the state floral
authority. Greenhouse peony flowers accelerate the ripening of
this spring bloomer, making it a hot-seller.
</P>
<P>
Heze currently has more than 1,800 peony greenhouses and 164
specialized floral enterprises, most of which are share-holding
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The county had 119 million yuan (14.3 million U.S. dollars) in
peony sales in 1997, with 3.8 million U.S. dollars of export
earnings. Last year's per-capita income in its Peony Township to
which floral planter Zhao Xiaodong belongs, exceeded 3,000 yuan.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
