<HEADLINE> Chinese Experts Invent New Fabric </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Experts in northwest China's
Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region have developed a new fabric that
resists ultraviolet rays and radiates infrared rays.
</P>
<P>
They note that the new material will be used to manufacture a
line of environmentally-friendly clothing.
</P>
<P>
Tests revealed that the high-quality fiber materials invented
by the Yinchuan Haoge Functional Materials Development Co. Ltd.,
resist 98 percent of ultraviolet rays and radiate more than 90
percent infrared ray. The fabric is nontoxic and nonallergenic.
</P>
<P>
Industrial emissions have seriously damaged the ozone layer,
with the irradiation of high volumes of ultraviolet rays leading
to a possible dramatic worldwide rise in skin diseases.
</P>
<P>
Clothing which resists ultraviolet rays has long been popular
in Europe and Japan. The new fabric in China is expected to become
a fashion item in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
