<HEADLINE> Communal Clash Claims Lives of 10 More in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 28 (Xinhua) -- About 10 more people have been
reportedly killed in the renewed bloody violence between rival
Ife and Modakeke communities in west Nigeria's Osun State.
</P>
<P>
The hostilities, which started early Monday morning, has
extended to adjourning villages, with the Ifes alleging that the
police killed their innocent kinsmen, The New Nigerian reported
today.
</P>
<P>
According to the official daily, seven people were killed by
some group of assailants believed to be Modakeke youths, while
the other three were killed by mobile policemen.
</P>
<P>
State Police Commissioner Sunday Aghedo confirmed that the
three persons were killed during a shoot-out between rioters and
mobile policemen, with three policemen including an officer
seriously wounded.
</P>
<P>
Total toll of the latest violence has been no fewer than 18
and about 50 other tribesmen from both communities were seriously
injured.
</P>
<P>
This is at least the fifth round of bloody violence in a
series since the first unrest was triggered off by the relocation
of the Ife-east local government headquarters from Modakeke to
Oke-Ogbo in Ile-Ife last August.
</P>
<P>
The clashes have claimed the lives of more than 100 people,
injured over 200 others and caused huge economic losses as many
houses were burnt and other properties damaged. 
</P>
