<HEADLINE> Howard Allows Free Vote in Constitutional Convention </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister John Howard
would allow a "conscience vote" for his coalition MPs at next
week's Constitutional Convention, that was believed to boost the
chances of Australia becoming a republic with a directly elected
president.
</P>
<P>
The move comes a week after the Australian Labor Party (ALP)'s
national conference backed away from its insistence that a
president be appointed by the parliament, and also gave the Labor
MPs the freedom to back a popularly elected president.
</P>
<P>
However, the National Party, the ruling partner of the Liberal
Party, still refused to bow to republican sentiment and at a
meeting Wednesday reaffirmed its support for the monarchy, and
urged its leadership to put this position at the forthcoming
convention.
</P>
<P>
Although Howard has warned that a directly elected president
would be a disastrous development, he had told the other 11
federal government members attending the convention that they were
free to vote as they saw fit.
</P>
<P>
Liberal MP Chris Gallus, one of only two publicly declared
republicans in the federal government delegation, said the prime
minister's move could allow the coalition MPs to back an elected
president, increasing the chances of Australia becoming a
republic.
</P>
<P>
While the federal opposition's six delegates are likely to vote
as a bloc at the convention, a spokesman for the Labor's
delegation said the national conference vote had freed up the
party's options.
</P>
<P>
"The conference has given the Labor MPs a considerable degree
of flexibility as to which republican model they support," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
However, the National Party MPs meeting in Canberra Wednesday
made clear Howard's statement would have no impact on them.
</P>
<P>
"The Parliamentary National Party meeting Wednesday in Canberra
reaffirmed the position of the National Party in support of the
existing Australian constitution," a statement released by the
party leader and Deputy Prime Minister Tim Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
"The party leadership would represent this position very
strongly at the Constitutional Convention." 
</P>
</TEXT>
