<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yunnan's Ethnic Economy Showing Healthy Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, January 28 (Xinhua) -- The ethnic areas of southwest
China's Yunnan Province have experienced a fast, healthy economic
growth in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Local statistics show that the annual growth rate in the gross
domestic product (GDP) in the ethnic areas was 11.5 percent for
the past five years, reaching 49.77 billion yuan (6.22 billion
U.S. dollars) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
This represents an increase of 0.6 percent over the provincial
average. And the GDP increased by 31.5 billion yuan (3.94 billion
U.S. dollars) over 1993.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the grain output of the provincial ethnic
areas grew from 5.83 million tons in 1993 to the present 6.78
million tons. The output of steel, raw coal, sugar, cigarettes and
generated energy have all increased more than 8 percent, according
to the statistics.
</P>
<P>
The annual sales volume in the ethnic areas has topped 13.4
percent with 15.36 billion yuan (1.92 billion U.S. dollars) in
1997, 5.5 billion yuan more than 1993.
</P>
<P>
Economists said these achievements should contribute to
increased efforts to tap local resources and to develop industries
with local characteristics.
</P>
<P>
Most of the province's ethnic groups are located in remote
areas with poor economic conditions. To promote economic progress
in these areas, Yunnan province annually invests more than one
billion yuan in the construction of water conservation
projects. Two-thirds of the investment is in the ethnic areas.
</P>
<P>
And 37 of the 76 medium- and large-size water control projects
under construction or completed are distributed in the
poverty-stricken ethnic areas.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen hydroelectric power stations are scheduled to be built
along the Lancang River, with a combined generating capacity of 22
million kilowatts.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Yunnan raised six billion yuan to build roads to
connect most of the towns and villages. Eight of 10 airports have
been put into operation, and seven of eight are in the ethnic
areas.
</P>
<P>
Telephones and mobile phones also have become readily available
in most of the ethnic areas.
</P>
<P>
The improved basic facilities have promoted border trade and
tourism in the ethnic areas and increased their overseas funds,
according to economists.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980128.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Economy Plays Major Role in Northwest China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, January 28 (Xinhua) -- The output value of the private
enterprises in northwest China's Guansu province reaches two
billion yuan every year.
</P>
<P>
This indicates that the private sector has emerged as a major
force in the local economy, officials said.
</P>
<P>
The province's 450,000 private enterprises now have 800,000
enmployees and a registered capital of 6 billion yuan (750 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Sources said that the number of private enterprises and
employees, their registered capital and output value have all
increased by 15 percent over 1992.
</P>
<P>
To develop the private sector, the province since 1994 has
provided favorable terms for private enterprises.
</P>
<P>
For example, the province has reduced the varieties of taxation
from 200 to 33.
</P>
<P>
To help private enterprises overcome difficulty, a special
organization was established jointly by 23 departments in June of
1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the province annually invests 800 million yuan (100
million U.S. dollars) in technical innovation for the private
sector. So far, 120 technical innovation projects have been
completed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
