<HEADLINE> Tourism Booming in East China City of Hangzhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Hangzhou, a major tourist city
in China, attracted 504,200 overseas tourists in 1997, up 9
percent over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The tourism sector of the city, capital of east China's
Zhejiang Province, earned 208 million U.S. dollars last year, an
increase of 20 percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
The city, one of China's seven ancient capital, is making great
efforts to become a tourist destination in the world. So far, it
has opened 100 scenic spots and historical sites to the outside
world, including the West Lake.
</P>
<P>
The city focused its efforts on the exploration and
construction of tourist resources. It has so far renovated more
than 40 scenic spots.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a tourism zone featuring folkways and buildings of
the Song Dynasty (960-1279) has been built. The city has also
built four museums for the exhibition of tea, silk, Chinese herbal
medicines and others.
</P>
<P>
The city has also held a series of tourism programs, which
represented the cultural and historical characters of the people
in southern China in ancient times, such as the West Lake Boat
Festival and the Hangzhou Holiday Tour '97.
</P>
<P>
To attract more domestic and overseas tourists, the city has
improved its infrastructure. The city has built 63 hotels.
</P>
<P>
Because of the improvements in traffic, hotels and other
tourist facilities, the city has great potential to absorb more
tourists from Hong Kong, Taiwan, Japan, the Republic of Korea, the
United States and some European countries, according to officials
from the city's tourism bureau. 
</P>
</TEXT>
