<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Investigation into last month's
alleged coup plot to overthrow Nigerian head of state Sani Abacha
came to an end, as the special investigation panel has submitted
its report to the government.
</P>
<P>
Acting defense spokesman Colonel Godwin Ugbo was quoted by
local media as saying here that the chief of defense staff,
Major-General Abdulsalam Abubakar received the report of the
15-man panel Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
General Abubakar reportedly said the findings of the panel
will be carefully looked into, with a view to implementing them.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said details of the panel's report will be made
public next week.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government announced the discovery of the alleged
coup plot on December 21, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Allegedly involved in the coup plot are the chief of general
staff, Lieutenant-General Oladipo Diya, Nigeria's number two
leader, former Minister of Communications Major-General Tajudeen
Olanrewaju, former Minister of Works and Housing, Major-General
Abdulkarim Adisa and nine others. they have since been put into
detention.
</P>
<P>
The panel headed by Major-General Chris Abutu Garuba has also
questioned 60 others.
</P>
<P>
All the coup suspects will be tried in a martial court, the
government has said.
</P>
<P>
Last December's coup is the second aimed at the military
government led by General Abacha. former head of state, General
Olusegun Obasanjo and others have been in jail since 1995 for
involvement in a coup. 
</P>
