<HEADLINE> Goodwill Abounds on Unforgettable Spring Festival Eve in Quake-hit Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Villagers in the
earthquake-ravaged Zhangjiakou Prefecture of north China's Hebei
Province spent an unforgettable Spring Festival eve on the ruins
of their hometown.
</P>
<P>
In Luanshishan Village of Zhangbei County, farmers had a
bonfire party together with soldiers participating in the relief
work to celebrate the Chinese Lunar New Year.
</P>
<P>
Amid the deafening sound of fireworks, gongs and drums,
villagers and soldiers were singing songs for the loving kindness
to farmers of the Communist Party of China (CPC) and the People's
Liberation Army (PLA), and people's profound gratitude to the
Party and the PLA.
</P>
<P>
Pop singers Sun Yue and Zang Tianshuo hurried from Beijing to
the quake-hit area and joined the gathering, providing an
unexpected surprise to farmers.
</P>
<P>
"I have never had such a happy festival as this in my
20-odd-year life. It is the PLA that has brought us pleasure, and
I will never forget the unusual eve of the Spring Festival," said
female farmer Yang Fenglan, dancing with a PLA man.
</P>
<P>
In the county's hospital, 150 villagers wounded in the quake
also received warm and tender support. Cao Zhengwang, a childless
elderly, was moved to tears when head nurse Yang Jinron brought
hot dumplings from her home to his bedside and fed him.
</P>
<P>
Hospital authorities had prepared meals for the wounded,
following local traditions to celebrate the festival.
</P>
<P>
Many local officials did not get a wink of sleep all night, as
they were busy visiting every family to make sure that all farmers
had sufficient goods and clothing during the cold season.
</P>
<P>
In Shizijie Village of Hailiutu Township, another moving story
spread rapidly. The quake left two brothers, Qiao Ying and Qiao
Ming, without parents. They became orphans overnight, and were
worried about where they would spend the festival.
</P>
<P>
But to their surprise, village officials had prepared rice,
flour and pork, as well as other daily necessities. "We will join
you to celebrate the festival," the village Party secretary Li
Qing told the two orphans.
</P>
<P>
However, officers of a military force stationed at the
quake-hit area sent for the brothers when they got the news. So,
Li and other village officials had to bow to the military's good
deed.
</P>
<P>
Early this morning, the Party secretary of the township's court
phoned the military force, saying that the province's Higher
People's Court asked him to make sure that the two brothers had
dumplings on the first day of the Spring Festival.
</P>
<P>
"We lost father and mother, but now we have more people so dear
to us," Qiao Ying said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
