<HEADLINE> Consultations Continue on ECOMOG's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom
Ikimi has started his second leg of consultations with west
African leaders on the future of the sub-regional peace-keeping
force known as ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
A foreign ministry release said Tuesday that Ikimi left the
capital Abuja the same day and was expected to parley with
leaders of Niger, Burkina Faso, the Gambia and Cote d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
He would also deliver special messages from Nigeria's head of
state General Sani Abacha, the current chairman of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS).
</P>
<P>
The minister has made a three-day visit to Togo, Guinea and
Liberia to consult with leaders there on the future role of
ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
According to the release, Ikimi will discuss with the leaders
on issues which are central to the security and stability of the
sub-region, and the possibility of reaching a compromise on the
peaceful resolution of the crisis in Sierra Leone within the
framework of the Conakry peace plan.
</P>
<P>
The peace accord signed last October in the Guinean capital
emphasizes the reinstatement of the legitimate government of
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, which was ousted in a military coup
on May 25 last year.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian minister is also expected to formally brief the
leaders on the recent change of ECOMOG force commander and
solicit the support of them for the new commander.
</P>
<P>
The visit was made at a time when Liberian President Charles
Taylor had said February 2 this year would be the deadline for
ECOMOG to wind up its operations in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
The first contingent of 1,205 Nigerian soldiers serving the
11,000-strong ECOMOG returned from Liberia last month under a
phased pullout plan.
</P>
<P>
Another batch of more than 1,200 Nigerian soldiers are due
back home this week.
</P>
<P>
Relations between President Taylor and former ECOMOG force
commander Maj.-gen. Victor Malu went sour over whether ECOMOG
should be involved in the restructuring and training of Liberia's
post-war army.
</P>
<P>
Taylor, who reportedly also refused ECOMOG to use Liberia as a
base to launch attacks against the military junta in neighboring
Sierra Leone, made an unscheduled visit to Nigeria late last year
to consult with the ECOWAS chairman over the alleged dispute.
</P>
<P>
Malu was recently recalled from Liberia and replaced by
another Nigerian officer, Maj.-gen. Timothy Shelpidi, but no
explanation was given for the change of the ECOMOG chief.
</P>
</TEXT>
