<HEADLINE> South China Province Continues Rapid Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 28 (Xinhua) -- The gross domestic product
(GDP) of south China's Guangdong Province was expected to reach
730.8 billion yuan (91.3 billion U.S. dollars) in 1997, a 10.6
percent rise over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that the retail price index of the
province, a native place for many overseas Chinese, increased by
0.1 percent, down 4.3 percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Guangdong harvested 19 million tons of grain,
an all-time high for the province. The agricultural output reached
162.3 billion yuan (20.3 billion U.S. dollars), up 5.7 percent
over 1996.
</P>
<P>
The industrial output was 1,240 billion yuan (155 billion
U.S. dollars). And 95.9 percent of industrial products are sold in
domestic and foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong, one of China's centers for foreign trade, achieved
127 billion U.S. dollars in imports and exports last year, up 15.5
percent over last year. And the exports reached 72 billion U.S.
dollars, an increase of 21.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Statistics also show that the province has invested 230 billion
yuan (29 billion U.S. dollars) in fixed assets in 1997, such as
the construction of Humen Bridge, Guangzhou Metro subway and some
water conservation projects. 
</P>
