<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Agriculture Forging Ahead in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, January 28 (Xinhua) -- The comprehensive growth of
agriculture in northwestern Gansu Province has played a vital role
in the take-off of local economy.
</P>
<P>
With the infusion of 70 million yuan (8.4 million US dollars)
from the central government, the province has exerted great effort
to raise 290 million yuan (34.9 million US dollars) to improve
agricultural conditions since it was listed as one of China's five
major comprehensive agricultural development zones in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Local statistics show that Gansu, with a territory of 45
million hectares, has the potential to explore 2.02 million
hectares of farmland, which is mainly distributed in the Gansu
Corridor.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, 43,000 medium- and low-yield fields have
been improved and 12,000 hectares of wasteland opened. And 12,000
hectares of irrigated areas were added.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the added grain and cotton production capacity
reached 127 million and 1.28 million kilograms, respectively. The
output of sugar and oil crops added 68.77 million and 3.24 million
kilograms. The per capita net income of farmers increased by more
than 160 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Gansu province has focused its attention on
accelerating the modernization process for agriculture.
</P>
<P>
More than 283,000 farmers in the province have received
technical training in agro-techniques, and improved varieties of
crops have been used on more than 90 percent of the farmland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
