<DOCNO> XIE19980128.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Port City in Guangxi Becomes Rising Star </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Fangchenggang, a newly built
port city in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, has
emerged as a rising star in pushing the region's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
With a coastline that stretches 584 kilometers, the city now
has built 25 berths, bringing to 8.5 million tons of annual
handling capacity. Ten of them are 10,000 ton-dead weight tonnage
(dwt) berths.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the city has invested 2.2 billion yuan
(275 million U.S. dollars) in the construction of wharfs and basic
facilities.
</P>
<P>
The city, also one of the country's four largest bases for the
export of cement, has forged trade ties with 159 ports in 64
countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Fangchenggang, which borders Vietnam, is considered the most
convenient passage to the sea in southwest China. Especially,
since the railway linked with the trunk line between Nanning,
capital of Guangxi, and Kunming, the capital of southwestern
Yunnan province, and Qinzhou-Fangchenggang expressway were put
into operation in 1997, more cargo can be exported throughout the
world.
</P>
<P>
To expand foreign trade, the city is exerting great efforts to
build markets exporting grain, fertilizer, building materials and
aquatic products near the wharves.
</P>
<P>
Apart from tourism, the city has paid close attention to
developing industries of raw materials, high-tech and
export-oriented processing sectors.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the city's annual growth rate of gross domestic
product reached 30.3 percent, much higher than the national
average. The annual handling capacity of the port city should
reach 20 million tons by the year 2000, according to the city's
plan for economic development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
