<HEADLINE> Rapid Growth, Low Inflation Mark Guangzhou Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 28 (Xinhua) -- The economy in Guangzhou,
capital of south China's Guangdong Province, was characterized by
rapid growth and low inflation in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Provincial statistics show that the city's gross domestic
product (GDP) reached 143.9 billion yuan (16.7 billion
U.S. dollars) during the January-November period, up 13.5 percent
over the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The city's retail sales had totaled 72.62 billion yuan (9.08
billion U.S. dollars) up to November, an increase of 16.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The service sector developed at a steady pace with a growth
rate of 2.69 percentage points higher that of the corresponding
period of 1996. The proportion of the service sector in the city's
GDP topped 47.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the city invested 34.75 billion (4.34
billion U.S. dollars) in fixed assets during the period, a 5.5
percent increase.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the south China city obtained revenues of
9.56 billion yuan (1.19 billion U.S. dollars), 25.2 percent more
than the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Forty percent of the city's small enterprises have adopted the
share-holding system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
