<DOCNO> XIE19980128.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Building Modern Enterprise System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 28 (Xinhua) -- China's largest industrial and
commercial center has made remarkable headway in the nationwide
reform program for building a modern enterprise system.
</P>
<P>
The 1,673 chosen pilot state-owned firms, which account for
more than 80 percent of the municipality's industrial asset value
of 648.7 billion yuan in 1997, have maintained a 10 percent annual
rate of increase in asset value during the past three years. The
asset-to-liability ratio in these firms has dropped from 80
percent to 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
Billions of yuan in idle state assets in 1,000 companies have
been re-used through bankruptcy and merger.
</P>
<P>
Apart from withdrawing government interference in the operation
of state-owned enterprises to make them more responsible for their
own profits and losses, the modern enterprise mechanism introduced
in Shanghai in 1993 has established a system of free choice for
employees.
</P>
<P>
This led to 1.39 million redundant laid-off workers. So far,
1.19 million of them have been re-employed because of the
"Re-employment Program" and social security systems that have been
set up in 95 percent of state-owned enterprises in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
In addition, state-owned enterprises began to select
decision-makers through competition rather than accepting
appointed managers. The two newly established talent-search
companies have recommanded 108 managers for state-owned
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
To specify a scientific measurement of the implementation of
the system, Shanghai has worked out 22 indices, and they all had
been met by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The modern enterprise system has injected great vitality to the
local economy. In 1997, Shanghai's per-capita gross domestic
product topped 3,000 U.S. dollars. The sales-to-output ratio for
major products reached 97 percent. Its industrial sector has
averaged a 14 percent growth rate for seven successive years.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai is striving to build itself into a base for new and
high-tech industries, which now account for two-thirds of the
municipality's total industrial output.
</P>
<P>
During the past three years, 32,000 new industrial products
have been introduced to fuel an annual product-replacement rate of
20 percent in Shanghai's industrial sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
