<HEADLINE> Turkey Plans to Buy 6 Sea Patrol Planes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has planned to buy six
sea patrol aircraft worth 250 million U.S. dollars to boost
its naval forces, local Daily News reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The plan was launched following the heightened tension in the
Aegean Sea with neighboring Greece, it said.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a general, who asked not be named, as
saying: "We must have a modern and high-capability fleet in the
Aegean and the Mediterranean in order to control the region."
</P>
<P>
He added that "new sea patrol aircraft will also help monitor
the passage and the type of load of any ship and monitor all
ships, including those involved in illegal immigration, between
Turkey and European countries."
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the type of the aircraft would be CASA
CN-235, which is being produced by the Turkish Aerospace
Industries (TAI) from a Spanish design and the vital avionic,
radar and weapon systems will be produced from abroad through a
bidding process.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Turkish naval force sent its 15 aged S-2E
aircraft into retirement after several decades of service.
</P>
<P>
Turkish and Greek warplanes and naval vessels are frequently
involved in minor frictions over and in the Aegean Sea.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, have long been at odds over several issues,
including the limits of airspace, rights of sea-bed mineral
resources as well as the protracted Cyprus issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
