<HEADLINE> African Police Chiefs to Meet in Kampala on Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, January 28 (Xinhua) -- A conference of police chiefs
from 10 east African countries on drug trafficking and crimes is
to be held in Kampala in February, "The New Vision" reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the conference, O.I. Mahita, the inspector general of
Tanzania, his Kenyan counterpart D.K. Wachira and his Ugandan
host John Cossy Odomel will hold a two-day first session to
prepare for the conference.
</P>
<P>
Delegations from Djiboudi, Ethiopia, Rwanda, Mauritius,
Seychelles, Sudan and Eritrea will attend the second session of
the conference to end on February 20. Burundi will be kept out
due to sanctions imposed on it by regional leaders.
</P>
<P>
Officials from Interpol Secretariat will be present as
observers.
</P>
<P>
Drug trafficking is a problem looming in Uganda in recent
years. Criminals use the country as an intermediate station to
send their drugs to South Africa, West Europe and North America.
</P>
<P>
Odomel earlier pledged to cooperate with Interpol and police
of other countries in the region through Interpol in fighting
against drug trafficking and other crimes. 
