<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Reduce Troops on Hokkaido Island </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, January 28 (Xinhua) -- The first deputy chief of
Japan's National Defense Agency, Masahiro Akiyama, said Tuesday
that two of the five ground divisions deployed in Hokkaido will be
reduced by half in line with the Guidelines of Defense Cooperation
for the 1996-2000 period.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Itar-Tass news agency, Akiyama said
that the number of tanks and other vehicles attached to those
units will also be reduced.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question on holding a U.S. Marines exercise in
Hokkaido in 1997, Akiyama said that it did not mean the
re-deployment of the U.S. troops from Okinawa to the area closer
to Russia.
</P>
<P>
It only meant the growth of the number of Japanese training
grounds where such exercises could be held, he added.
</P>
<P>
Akiyama had a four-and-a-half-hour talk with Russian Defense
Minister Igor Sergeyev on bilateral military cooperation Monday.
</P>
<P>
He described the talk as major success, the Itar-Tass said.
</P>
<P>
Akiyama arrived here for a working visit on Saturday. 
</P>
