<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yield of Crops Down in Kenya due to El Nino Rains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Kenya will register a sharp
reduction of maize, wheat, sugar and coffee due to heavy rains
and floods caused by the El Nino weather phenomenon, local press
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
As a result of El Nino rains during harvesting period last
year, farmers lost over a million bags of maize and nearly
600,000 bags of wheat, leaving a shortfall of at least seven bags
of maize this year which have to be met through imports.
</P>
<P>
The net realized production for long rains was 22.7 million
bags (90 kg per bag) of maize and 2.5 million of wheat, according
to the latest data from the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The sugar production will also fall to 350,000 tons this year,
from 390,000 tons in 1997 and 400,000 tons in 1996. The gap is
attributed to lack of cane collection because of poor roads and
cane from farms with low sugar content.
</P>
<P>
Consumption locally has remained at 560,000 tons in the last
two years and the authorities do not foresee a change this year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, coffee production is forecast to reduce to 65,000
tons in 1997/98 (October/September) from 68,000 tons in the
previous year because of the bad weather.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains have devastated a majority part of irrigation
schemes nationwide, leaving more than 300,000 farm families
suffering with their crops washed away. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
