<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-28 08:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Offers Reward for Information on Lost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Israel has offered a reward
for any information about the Israeli submarine Dakar which
disappeared under mysterious circumstances 30 years ago, local
newspaper Haaretz Reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It quoted Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai as saying
that Israel is offering a reward "to any person, in Israel or
elsewhere, for information that will enable the submarine Dakar
to be located."
</P>
<P>
The Dakar left Portsmouth, England, for Israel on January 9,
1968. The last contact with the vessel was made between January 24
and 25, when it was in the Mediterranean Basin. Sixty-nine people
were on board the Dakar when it vanished.
</P>
<P>
A search operation was mounted immediately after it had become
clear that the submarine had disappeared, and it was officially
listed as missing on February 4, 1968.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai decided on the reward in principle two weeks ago,
and made the final decision early this week after consulting with
Israeli Army Chief of Staff Ammon Lipkin-Shahak and Navy
Commander Alex Tal. But he did not specify the amount of the
reward.
</P>
<P>
At the annual state memorial ceremony for the missing
submarine held in Jerusalem Tuesday, Shahak said that "Israel
Army has no weightier, more important or more authentic duty than
to bring back the fighters of the Dakar and the other fighters
who have not found a final resting place."
</P>
<P>
Tal also said at the ceremony that he had taken part in
searches for the Dakar as a young officer, but had never imagined
that 30 years later he would still not be able to offer an
authoritative account of what happened. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
