<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Nepali Supreme Court Faces Hard Choice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's Supreme Court is
challenged with three different opinions concerning the issue of
whether to dissolve parliament and call mid-term polls, or to
convene a special parliamentary session to discuss a no-confidence
motion against the present government.
</P>
<P>
At the week-long discussions which ended on Tuesday, eight of
the 14 amicus curiae (friends of the court) and representatives
from political parties who had aired their views supported Prime
Minister Surya Bahadur Thapa's recommendation to dissolve
parliament and call fresh polls.
</P>
<P>
Five favored the petition by 96 MPs to call a special session
of parliament to discuss their censure motion against the present
coalition government while one stated unequivocally that the
question does not actually fall under the jurisdiction of the
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
The latest political crisis in the country started on January 8
when the prime minister, who came to power last October, made the
abrupt call for dissolution of parliament to preempt the move by
96 MPs from the main opposition Communist Party of Nepal (United
Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML) and his own party.
</P>
<P>
After days of discussions with advisors, legal experts and
party leaders over the two clashing petitions which are both
constitutional, King Birendra could not make a decision and
referred the matter to the apex court on January 13, the first
time for him to do so.
</P>
<P>
During the discussions in the court which began on January 19,
some amicus curiae and representatives from the three ruling
parties stood behind Thapa, arguing that the constitution has
provided for the dissolution of parliament as a privilege of the
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
They added that Thapa recommended dissolution well before the
submission seeking a special session, so the prime minister's
should take precedence.
</P>
<P>
They also argued that the King must consult with the prime
minister before acting upon anything except matters specifically
reserved to his discretion.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-UML retorted that parliament is the mother giving birth
to prime minister, any attempt to save her must be credited, and
the dissolution is possible only when there is no other option.
</P>
<P>
Former President of Nepal Bar Association Krishna Prasad Pant
said the King is bound to convene a special session of the Lower
House as long as the House is alive. He also disagreed with the
logic that the King should consult the cabinet even in simply
subjective questions.
</P>
<P>
"A constitutional monarch can't be supposed to act like a
robot, who doesn't work without guidance," he said.
</P>
<P>
Former Attorney General Motikaji Sthapit questioned the court's
jurisdiction, saying it had been asked to "suggest priorities for
the execution of an entirely executive duty."
</P>
<P>
Several advocates of constitutional law had advised that the
court remain aloof from the act of determining anything as the
issue is "entirely political."
</P>
<P>
Press reports said the nine-member special bench of the apex
court has asked the amicus curiae to furnish written briefs of
their arguments along with relevant reference materials by Friday
before the bench can come up with an opinion for the King.
</P>
<P>
The country's constitution Stipulates that "If His Majesty
wishes to have an opinion of the Supreme Court on any complicated
legal question of interpretation of this Constitution or of any
other law, it shall upon consideration on the question, report to
His Majesty its opinion thereon."
</P>
<P>
But observers say the court faces a really hard choice.
</P>
<P>
The court had spun a cocoon around itself by handing down two
conflicting verdicts.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, it ruled that Prime Minister Girija Prasad Koirala of
the Nepali Congress was within his constitutional authority to
recommend dissolution of parliament and holding of fresh polls.
</P>
<P>
But the following year, it overturned the similar
recommendation made to the King by Prime Minister Man Mohan
Adhikari of the CPN-UML, ruling that dissolution was not allowed
if an alternative government could be formed from the existing
parliament.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980128.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-28 </DATE_TIME>
