<HEADLINE> Chinese Walks on Wire to Celebrate Spring Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Adili, who set the Guinness
world record with a daring feat of walking the wire across China's
longest Yangtze River last year, walked on high wire again here
today to celebrate the Chinese traditional Spring festival.
</P>
<P>
The famed professional tightrope walker pulled off a series of
eye-popping acrobatics on a 120-meter long wire, which was
stretched between two 80-meter-high towering pillars in the
National Olympic Sports Center in the northern Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The highlight of the 10-minute show came when Adili defied the
gravity by displaying the traditional dances of his hometown,
China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The 27-year-old Uygur said after the performance that he was
sending greetings in his own way to the Beijing residents, who are
celebrating the Chinese traditional new year -- Spring Festival.
</P>
<P>
Adili, the seventh generation of a high-walking family from
Xinjing, earned his fame last June when he crossed the Yangtze
River on a 640.75-meter steel wire stretching 375 meters high in a
time of 13 minutes and 48 seconds. 
</P>
