<HEADLINE> Killer Epidemic Out of Control in Kenya, Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 28 (Xinhua) -- The International Committee of
the Red Cross (ICRC) says the spread of Rift Valley fever, a
haemorrhagic disease that has killed more than 500 people in
north-eastern Kenya and southern Somalia, is "out of control".
</P>
<P>
The epidemic has spread from Kenya's northern Wajir and
Garissa districts to eastern Marsabit and Isiolo, local press
reported Tuesday. The death toll is believed higher than the
Kenyan government and the U.N. sources have claimed.
</P>
<P>
The vastness of the affected area combined with the refusal by
striking governmental nurses to return to work have contributed
to the rising death toll.
</P>
<P>
The nurses are seeking a 300 percent pay hike citing excessive
work load, poor remuneration and hazards of their work place as
grievances.
</P>
<P>
The fever, which is transmitted from infected livestock to man
through handling or eating infected flesh and which can also be
transmitted by mosquito, broke out in the regions in the wake of
heavy floods caused by El Nino rains.
</P>
<P>
Most affected areas have been rendered inaccessible by road
and the true extent of the disease remains unknown.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ICRC predicted an immediate major "cholera
crisis" in the whole of eastern Africa where already more than
4,000 people have perished since floods overwhelmed the
sanitation system in the region last October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
