<HEADLINE> Cities Celebrate Spring Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 28 (Xinhua) -- A warm Spring Festival
atmosphere has settled in nationwide, but with different
characteristics in different cities.
</P>
<P>
Cake, cigarettes and wine once were popular gifts to relatives
and friends during the festival, followed by flowers and food
items, but these are no longer fashionable in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Instead, local residents prefer to send green vegetables packed
in plastic bags. Boxes or bags of clean vegetables such as cherry
radishes, balsam apples, Japanese yams and Israeli green peppers,
at varying prices between 10 to 120 yuan, are selling well in the
markets.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Beijing residents have other choices to spend the
holidays, such as lantern shows, fairs, dinners and travel.
</P>
<P>
People in Wuhan, capital of central China's Hubei Province,
tend to celebrate the festival in the traditional way. Some 60
percent of local residents consider the Lunar New Year as the most
important festival of the year, according to a recent
survey. Eighty-four percent of them chose to have holiday meals
with their families, and 55 percent planned to stay up late or all
night on the eve.
</P>
<P>
In Chongqing, a newly promoted municipality directly under the
central govenment in southwest China, new and clean buses took
people by surprise on the eve of the Spring Festival. The city
began to replace its dirty old buses with new ones, and has
converted 60 of the 120 diesel-engine buses to petroleum. The city
will add another 200 new buses this year.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin in north China enjoys a strong cultural flavor during
the holidays. High on the purchase list of many families are books
for children, VCD discs and flower bouquets.
</P>
<P>
And in Lhasa, capital of Tibet Autonomous Region, residents are
happy to have stable market prices. A fair at the foot of the
Potala Palace sells green vegetables, fresh fish and prawns.
"Market prices this year are lower than last year and, more
importantly, you can buy whatever you want," a woman named Luo
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
