<HEADLINE> Samaranch Assures Nagano of Olympic Rewards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 28 (Xinhua) -- International Olympic Committee
(IOC) president Juan Antonio Samaranch assured Nagano Wednesday
that its huge investment in the upcoming Winter Olympics would pay
off.
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that the Japanese sport movement, Nagano City
and its prefecture will be the main beneficiary of this long term
investment," he said in a statement on arrival in Nagano.
</P>
<P>
"I am happy to be in Nagano and look forward to a very
successful Olympic Winter Games," the 77-year-old Olympic chief
said. "The preparation of the Games was implemented according to
schedule."
</P>
<P>
Nagano had to build a dozen stadia and facilities financed
mostly through bond issues, which cost each family more than two
million yen (about 15,000 dollars).
</P>
<P>
Total investment is estimated at 1,650 billion yen (13.8
billion dollars), including super-fast rail and road links, with
the central government picking up just half the tab for Olympic
facilities.
</P>
<P>
More than two billion yen (15 million dollars) is expected to
be spent each year in the upkeep of what a citizens watchdog in
Nagano called the "ruins of the Olympics."
</P>
<P>
"Most important, we have enough roads to venues," Samaranch
said as he arrived at Nagano central station by a high-speed
"bullet train" from Tokyo after flying in from Europe earlier in
the day.
</P>
<P>
The rail service was opened in October as part of preparations
for the biggest Winter Games involving competitors from an
estimated 74 countries and featuring 68 events, both record
figures.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch noted that curling, snowboard and women's ice hockey
were included in the Olympic program for the first time. Some
2,450 athletes are expected to compete in the last Winter Games of
the century.
</P>
<P>
Samarach was also scheduled to preside over the IOC executive
board and general meetings beginning on Friday in Nagano, 200
kilometers northwest of Tokyo. 
</P>
