<HEADLINE> Northwest China Province Increases GDP by 9 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, January 28 (Xinhua) -- The gross domestic product (GDP)
in northwest China's Qinghai Province is expected to increase by 9
percent in 1997 when all date has been compiled.
</P>
<P>
Qinghai, a sparely populated area on the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau,
should record a total grain output of 1.28 million tons, up 2.86
percent over the previous year. And the output of oil crops
bearing is expected to increase by 5.88 percent to 180,000 tons,
according to a provincial official.
</P>
<P>
He said the province's township-run enterprises should realize
3.8 billion yuan (475 million U.S. dollars) of production value,
up 25.5 percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
The per capita net income for farmers is estimated to reach
1,320 yuan (165 U.S. dollars) in 1997, a 12.5 percent increase
over 1996. And an additional 168,000 farmers earned enough to rise
above the poverty level in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The official said the province's industrial output should
increase 10.84 percent to 11.1 billion yuan (1.8 billion
U.S. dollars). The building industry alone increased 20.6 percent
in output.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the province invested 9.7 billion yuan (1.2 billion
U.S. dollars) in fixed assets in 1997, 24.9 percent more than
1996, he added.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the Qinghai Oil Field has proven natural
gas deposits of 150 billion cubic meters and can produce 1.6
million tons of crude oil annually.
</P>
<P>
The province invested 1.3 billion yuan in completing 33 major
technological innovation projects in 1997, up 24.8 percent over
the previous year. At the same time, 355 million yuan was invested
in the construction of roads, he said. 
</P>
