<HEADLINE> Australia Govt Urged to Act on Long-term Unemployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Australia's biggest seniors
group Wednesday called for government action to reduce the number
of the older and long-term unemployed people.
</P>
<P>
Despite an overall fall in the number of unemployment,
Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) figures produced for the
National Seniors Association (NSA) showed a sharp rise in the
number and proportion of people aged over 50 who had been jobless
for more than a year, NSA chief executive David Deans said.
</P>
<P>
While one in three jobless Australians were now considered
long-term unemployed, the rate rose to over one in two for those
aged over 50.
</P>
<P>
"While things are bad for the unemployed, they're twice as bad
for people aged 50 and over," Deans said in a statement available
here.
</P>
<P>
The December ABS figures showed 67,200 men and 28,200 women
aged over 50 had been looking for work for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that employers in the public and private sectors
have failed to recognize the benefits of employing and retaining
older workers," Deans said. "It is also clear that only government
action and leadership can address this issue and help stop this
shameful waste of talent and experience."
</P>
<P>
Deans said he had written to federal Employment Minister David
Kemp to alert him to the group's concern.
</P>
<P>
"While recognizing these measures would require a significant
investment on the part of government, NSA argues the cost of
consigning almost 100,000 people aged 50 and over to the
unemployment scrapheap costs the nation more through social
security payments, health problems and other indirect costs," he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
