<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Growth Rate of China's Exports to Japan Slows in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 28 (Xinhua) -- China's exports to Japan are
undergoing major changes because of the new international economic
situation, a trade newspaper has reported.
</P>
<P>
An article carried by the Beijing-based International Trade
News said the Sino-Japanese trade volume in 1997 grew by only 1.2
percent over 1996, compared with 8.6 percent the previous year.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the annual growth rate of
Sino-Japanese trade volume remained more than 30 percent during
the 1993-95 period.
</P>
<P>
Last year's financial crisis in Southeast Asia resulted in the
depreciation of the exchange rates of these currencies with the
Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, the exchange rate of Renminbi yuan, China's
currency, with the Japanese yen did not devalue at all, but went
higher. This created an unfavorable situation for Chinese exports
to Japan.
</P>
<P>
Statistics of the Japanese Finance Ministry show that the
growth rate of China's exports to Japan in November was 1.3
percent. Compared with September the export volume in food,
textiles, electronics, machinery and other traditional products
declined.
</P>
<P>
Direct investment in China from Japanese firms continued to
fall in 1997. In comparison, Japanese investment in China grew
more than 20 percent during the 1991-95 period.
</P>
<P>
The report called for a readjustment of China's policy
concerning exports to Japan and efforts to create new market
potential to better cope with the ever-changing economic
situation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
