<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Financial Crisis Has Organizers in Review Mode </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 278 (Xinhua) -- The Asian financial crisis
and its possible effects on Australian and international sponsors
of the Sydney Olympics have forced Games organizers to review
their budget.
</P>
<P>
Olympic organizers also conceded Wednesday that transport will
form a daunting task during the Games.
</P>
<P>
Sandy Hollway, chief executive of the Sydney Organizing
Committee for the Olympic Games (SOCOG), said Wednesday that the
body was not alarmed by the crisis but wanted to take a "prudent"
look at the potential effects it could have on Games sponsors.
</P>
<P>
"So I'm not coming at this from the point of view of alarm
about our financial position at all but certainly realism," he
said. "If there is going to be a problem I would like to
anticipate it.
</P>
<P>
"I don't see a new budget coming out. We are very concerned to
stay within budget revenue and expenditure."
</P>
<P>
Hollway said none of the sponsors had told SOCOG they would
have to pull out of their commitments to the 2000 Games because of
the crisis. He said he hoped to have reviewed budget forecasts
ready by the middle of this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a transport report released Wednesday shows that
Sydney's rail network will be forced to handle 80 percent more
people during the 2000 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney 2000 Olympic and Paralympic Transport Strategic Plan
also predicts more than 500,000 people will travel to Sydney
Olympic Park at Homebush in the city's west on the busiest day of
the Games.
</P>
<P>
Traffic flows are also expected to be heavy, with Victoria Road
now identified as the key route linking the city and Olympic
facilities.
</P>
<P>
Olympic transit lanes will be established on Victoria Road,
dedicated for use by athletes, official Olympic vehicles and
public transport, including bus services and taxis.
</P>
<P>
Olympics Minister Michael Knight said the transport problems
facing Sydney and Olympic organizers were enormous and the stakes
high.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney rail network, which moves almost one million people
a day, will bear the brunt of spectator transportation for the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that with the combined pressure of the Olympics
and general daily commuting it will move 1.8 million people each
24 hours during the Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
