<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Withdraw Troops from Streets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, January 28 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government is
withdrawing soldiers from law enforcement duties in Harare and
nearby Chitungwiza where they had helped end violence and looting
following last week's food riots.
</P>
<P>
In a statement Tuesday, a government spokesman said normalcy
had returned to both Harare and Chitungwiza and that the army
would be pulled out.
</P>
<P>
"As a result, details from the Zimbabwe National Army, who had
been deployed to assist the Zimbabwe Republic Police will now be
withdrawn from the streets but will remain on standby and can be
redeployed should the need arise," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The police, on the other hand, will remain on the ground to
continue with investigations as the process of apprehending
culprits and recovering looted property continues, added the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The army came to the aid of the police, who were outnumbered
and were encountering logistical problems in quelling the wave of
violence and looting which swept through Harare's high-density
suburbs and Chitungwiza on Monday and Tuesday last week.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said, "both the army and police wish to
reiterate that no single shot was fired by the army in the entire
exercise and extend their deep appreciation for the cooperation
received from the public."
</P>
<P>
Last week's violent food riots which brought business to a
halt in Harare and Chitungwiza, have seen about 2,575 people
being arrested for looting and public violence during the
disturbances which later spilled, but to a much lesser extent, to
other centers throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
About 1,748 suspects have so far been brought before the
courts. To cope with the increasing number of suspects being
brought before the courts, special arrangements have been made to
allow courts to sit as late as 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
From Monday to Wednesday, thousands of residents in Harare,
Chitungwiza and other small towns staged demonstrations in
protest against recent prices increases.
</P>
<P>
Some of them looted shops, stoned cars and destroyed property,
causing millions of Dollars losses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
