<HEADLINE> MNLF, MILF Settle Conflict in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 28 (Xinhua) -- The Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF) announced Wednesday that it has settled its conflict
with the former rebel Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) in the
Southern Philippines after seven people were killed in a fighting.
</P>
<P>
According to Philippine News Agency reports, MILF vice-chairman
Ghadzali Jaafar personally initiated the settlement together with
his MNLF counterpart Randy Karon.
</P>
<P>
The agency said the Moro parties agreed to send a letter to the
government army, requesting the army's Sixth Infantry Division in
Maguindanao, the Southern Philippines, not to intervene anymore
when future conflicts take place between the MILF and the MNLF.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, an army soldier, five MILF rebels and one civilian
were killed after MILF rebels ambushed government troops who tried
to intervene in fighting between the two Moro groups.
</P>
<P>
In retaliation, the government troops fired back with cannon
shells, killing five MILF rebels.
</P>
<P>
The MNLF and the government signed a peace accord in September
1996 and part of MNLF forces has been integrated into the army and
the national police. But the MILF rejected the peace accord and is
continuing its fighting for an independent Muslim state in the
Southern Philippines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
