<HEADLINE> ADB Extends Loans to Indonesia, Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 28 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
Wednesday approved a 32 million U.S. dollar loan to Indonesia for
a conservation project, and two loans of 24.5 million dollars to
the Philippines to help its disadvantaged children.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement issued here, the Manila-based bank said
prospects for conservation of biodiversity and improvement of the
livelihood of over 120,000 people will be greatly enhanced with a
Central Sulawesi Integrated Area Development and Conservation
Project in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The bank's loan to Indonesia will come from its ordinary
capital resources and will be repayable within 25 years, including
a grace period of 7 years, it said.
</P>
<P>
In a separate press statement, the ADB said half of the
Philippines' most disadvantaged and vulnerable children under six
will benefit from an Early Childhood Development Project, for
which two loans totaling 24.5 million dollars will be granted by
the bank.
</P>
<P>
The project will substantially lower infant and child
mortality, malnutrition and primary school dropout rates among 2.7
million children in the regions of Western Visayas, Central
Visayas and Central Mindanao, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
According to the ADB, the total project cost is estimated at 65
million dollars. Apart from the 24.5 million dollars, the World
Bank will provide 22.4 million dollars, local government units 6.4
million dollars and the national government 11.7 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The ADB loans will be repayable over 25 years, including a
grace period of five years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
