<HEADLINE> Hingis Into Semi-finals in Australian Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 28 (Xinhua) -- World No.1 Martina Hingis
swept past fifth seed Mary Pierce 6-2, 6-3 Wednesday to set up a
semi-final showdown on Thursday at Australian Open tennis
tournament against 10th seeded German Anke Huber.
</P>
<P>
Today's 59 minute match was almost flawless display for Hingis
and Pierce's too many unforced errors cost her chance into the
semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
Huber became the first player to enter the semi-finals of the
tournament in Melbourne today with a victory over Arantxa Sanchez
Vicario.
</P>
<P>
The 10th-seeded German won 7-6 (9-7), 7-5 and probably ended
any chance the Spaniard had of winning an Australian championship.
</P>
<P>
Sanchez Vicario, who was making her eighth consecutive
appearance in Australian Open, has played in three semi-finals and
two finals.
</P>
<P>
Today's loss, though, made it three years in a row that the
seventh seed has failed to advance beyond the quarters.
</P>
<P>
At the age of 23 years and without a grand slam title to her
credit, Huber must also have only limited opportunities.
</P>
<P>
But she has the best chance of her career to win one in
Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
Huber meets top seed Martina Hingis in tomorrow's semi-final
after the Swiss teen beat Frenchwoman Mary Pierce 6-3, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
The German always had the upper hand today and said she adopted
new tactics after winning only one match in her previous 11
meetings with Sanchez Vicario.
</P>
<P>
"Today I played the way I wanted to from the beginning. I was
patient and waited for my chances," Huber said.
</P>
<P>
The pair battled for almost two hours before Huber grabbed the
third of her match point opportunities, settling the issue with a
perfectly placed backhand into the corner.
</P>
<P>
For Sanchez Vicario, the defeat left the impression that she
may have lost the edge to her two greatest assets, speed and
determination.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish No.1 won her three grand slam titles by grinding
down her opponents and hunting down every ball.
</P>
<P>
In her past year, though, more of them are slipping by out of
reach. 
</P>
</TEXT>
