<HEADLINE> Rios out duels Berasategui for semifinal berth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Ninth seed Marcelo Rios of
Chile outgunned Spanish baseliner Alberto Berasategui in four sets
at the Australian Open in Melbourne on Wednesday to reach his
first grand slam semifinal.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old left-hander from Santiago got off to a slow
start against the Spanish dangerman but quickly regained the
initiative to complete an impressive 6-7 (6-8), 6-4, 6-4, 6-0 win.
</P>
<P>
Rios struggled for accuracy in the first set but soon found
range with his forehands and backhands from the baseline, pushing
the 1994 French Open runner-up from one side of Melbourne Park's
centre court to another.
</P>
<P>
Berasategui had been in giant-killing form earlier in the
tournament, toppling second seed Patrick Rafter of Australia and
former world number one Andre Agassi.
</P>
<P>
The pony-tailed Rios made the quarter-finals in Melbourne and
at the U.S. Open last year. He and Czech veteran Petr Korda are
the only two seeded players left in the Open men's draw.
</P>
<P>
World number eight Rios will meet either Nicolas Kiefer of
Germany or Frenchman Nicolas Escude in the semifinals, the two
unseeded Europeans due to meet in the last quarter-final later on
Wednesday. 
</P>
