<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Not to Declare Debt Moratorium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will not follow
Indonesia by declaring a debt moratorium, cabinet members have
said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has announced a temporary freeze on servicing a
corporate debt estimated at 66 billion dollars, raising fears that
Thailand would follow suit.
</P>
<P>
The Thai cabinet met on Tuesday to work out steps following
Indonesia's decision, which prompted Standard and Poor's, the U.S.
ratings agency, to downgrade 19 Indonesian Corporations, according
to the Bangkok Post today.
</P>
<P>
Thai cabinet members made it clear that events in Indonesia
would not affect Thailand's public debt standing and the ability
to repay. Thailand' foreign debt stands at about 90 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
If there were to be any impact at all, "It would only be
minimal," a cabinet member was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Thai Finance Minister Tarrin Mimmanhaeminda said Indonesia's
debt crisis would not dampen investment confidence in Thailand
which was in better shape than Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The weight of the crisis hitting the two countries was clearly
distinguishable, Tarrin said.
</P>
<P>
The baht had depreciated 100 percent against the dollar while
the Indonesian rupiah downgraded 400 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said Thailand remained committed to the fulfillment of IMF
loan obligations despite the difficulty Thailand was facing.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has asked the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to
ease a key condition for a 17.2-billion-dollar rescue package
which requires a budget surplus equivalent to one percent of gross
domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the IMF said the organization has agreed to
ease key conditions to reflect Thailand's actual economic
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Thai officials will hold talks with an IMF team from February
2-14 for a quarterly review of progress in implementing the
package.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
