<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Croatia President Pleased With Achievements in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, January 27 (Xinhua) -- President Franjo Tudjman of the
Republic of Croatia Tuesday has spoken highly of the government's
achievements last year.
</P>
<P>
"Last year has been marked by the full achievement of the
fundamental goal of Croatian national and State policy," Tudjman
said at the beginning of his report.
</P>
<P>
He said 1997 saw the country maintaining stability in all
aspects, with the living standards of people improved and its
economy rejuvenated and developing.
</P>
<P>
The most important achievement of 1997 is the unification of
the country with its eastern part through peaceful measures, he
stressed. The unification fulfilled the dream of the people for
one century.
</P>
<P>
These achievements improved Croatia's international prestige
remarkably, he said.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the crises in Bosnia-Herzegovina, Tudjman said
his country's principle is that the Washington and Dayton
Agreements must be realized to "assure a truly constituent and
equal position to the Croatian people" in the republic, and to
protect the national interests of his country.
</P>
<P>
"In relation to current integration trends in Europe, and to
decisions regarding the expansion of Euro-Atlantic institutions,
Croatia should put every possible effort into becoming an integral
part of such developments as soon and as extensively as possible,"
the president said.
</P>
<P>
Croatia was also seeking a membership of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization and the World Trade Organization, he said.
</P>
<P>
The main target of the country for this year is promote
stability and confidence in the country and renovate the economy
and improve the country's international status, he concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
