<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Will Add More Teachers to Shrink Classes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 27 (Xinhua) -- United States President Bill
Clinton said on Tuesday that his nation will add 100,000 new
teachers to reduce class sizes in schools in an effort to achieve
his 21st education plan.
</P>
<P>
He also proposed a school construction tax cut to help
communities modernize, or build, 5,000 schools to meet the smaller
class requirement.
</P>
<P>
Clinton made the proposal in his annual State of the Union
address delivered to Congress Tuesday night. In the speech, the
president emphasized that his administration would regard
education as the nation's highest priority in an effort to meet
the requirements of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
In last year's State of the Union address, Clinton stressed
that education was the nation's highest priority and he laid out a
ten-point plan to upgrade the nation's education.
</P>
<P>
His administration and Congress have worked out plans to
increase public school choice by adding 3,000 charter schools,
connecting classrooms to the information superhighways, increasing
scholarships, and launching programs to help schools make sure
every school child can read. 
</P>
</TEXT>
