<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Saving Social Security Before Spending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 27 (Xinhua) -- United States President Bill
Clinton delivered a State of the Union address Tuesday evening,
calling on Congress to "save Social Security first" before
spending any budget surpluses.
</P>
<P>
"Tonight I propose we reserve 100 percent of the surplus --
that's every penny of any surplus -- until we have taken all the
measures necessary to strengthen the Social Security system for
the 21st century," he said in his annual nationwide address.
</P>
<P>
To promote a solution to Social Security's problems, Clinton
proposed a White House conference in December, which would allow
him to spend the year talking about saving Social Security while
delaying decisions until after the mid-term elections.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the country's economic situation, Clinton noted,
"the state of our union is strong" with the lowest unemployment in
24 years and the lowest inflation in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
The president urged Congress to raise the minimum wage from
5.15 U.S. dollars an hour at present, but did not specify by how
much.
</P>
<P>
"Because these times are good, we can afford to take one
simple, sensible step to help millions of workers struggling to
provide for their families," he added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also urged raising the price of cigarettes by 1.50
dollars a pack to deter teen smoking, and said tobacco companies
should be slapped with penalties "if they continue marketing to
kids".
</P>
<P>
He urged 21.7 billion dollars for a child-care initiative,
doubling to two million the number of children eligible for
child-care subsidies.
</P>
<P>
He proposed 7.3 billion dollars to hire 100,000 teachers, with
a goal of reducing class sizes in grades one to three. He also
urged tax credits to pay interest on nearly 22 billion dollars in
bonds to build and renovate public schools.
</P>
<P>
With the economy booming and the government collecting more tax
revenue, Clinton claimed that he would submit a balanced budget
for 1999, three years earlier than required in his deal with
Congress.
</P>
<P>
"And if we hold fast to fiscal discipline, we may balance the
budget this year, four years ahead of schedule," he said.
</P>
<P>
With Asia undergoing a financial crisis, Clinton requested 18
billion dollars to boost the International Monetary Fund (IMF). He
also asked for more than one billion dollars to pay the U.S. debt
to the United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
