<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges Medicare Extension to Aged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 27 (Xinhua) -- United States President
Bill Clinton said on Tuesday Congress should let Americans between
the ages of 55 and 65 buy into the Medicare system.
</P>
<P>
In his State of the Union address, Clinton said: "It won't add
a dime to the deficit, but the peace of mind it will provide will
be priceless."
</P>
<P>
Clinton also wanted Congress to extend tax deductions for
working families.
</P>
<P>
He said if lawmakers pass his plan, a family of four with an
income of 35,000 dollars and high child care costs would not pay
anything in federal income taxes.
</P>
<P>
The president proposed that Congress extend the Family and
Medical Leave Act to cover an additional 10 million workers. He
said lawmakers should extend the law to give parents time off for
parent-teacher conferences and doctor's visits.
</P>
<P>
"We must help parents protect their children from the gravest
health threat that they face: an epidemic of teen smoking spread
by multi-million dollar marketing campaigns," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
He urged Congress to pass bipartisan, comprehensive legislation
that will improve public health, protect tobacco farmers, and
change the way tobacco companies do business forever.
</P>
<P>
Clinton called on Congress to raise the price of cigarettes by
up to 1.50 dollars a pack over the next 10 years, with penalties
if tobacco companies continue marketing to children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
