<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Asks Congress to Support his Foreign Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
asked Congress on Tuesday to support his foreign policies ranging
from the expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) to paying debts to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"Within days, I will ask the Senate for its advice and consent
to make Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic the newest members
of NATO," said Clinton in his annual State of the Union address.
"I ask the Senate to say yes to them -- our new allies."
</P>
<P>
"By taking in new members and working closely with new
partners, including Russia and Ukraine, NATO can help to assure
that Europe is a stronghold for peace in the 21st Century," said
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Last July at its special summit in Madrid, NATO decided to
accept Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic as new members by
1999. The decision needs to be approved by a two-thirds majority
vote in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also urged Congress to agree to paying off some 1.4
billion U.S. dollars dues it owes to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"It's long past time to make good on our debt to the United
Nations. More and more, we are working with other nations to
achieve common goals," he said.
</P>
<P>
"If we want America to lead, we must set a good example. As we
see so clearly in Bosnia, allies who share our goals can share our
burdens. In this new era, our freedom and independence are
actually enriched, not impoverished, by our increasing
interdependence with other nations," he added.
</P>
<P>
In a legislation last year, Congress voted for paying the
arrears to the U.N. with conditions setting benchmarks for the
reforms of the world body.
</P>
<P>
The conditions were opposed by the Clinton administration and
strongly criticized by U.N. members.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Bosnia, Clinton appealed Congress to support
further deployment of U.S. troops in the region. He decided last
month that the GIs will continue to stay in Bosnia beyond the
deadline of June when mandate of the current Stabilization Forces
expires.
</P>
<P>
"I will ask Congress to continue its support for our troops and
their mission in Bosnia," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The progress is unmistakable -- but not yet irreversible. To
take firm root, Bosnia's fragile peace still needs the support of
American and allied troops when the current NATO mission ends in
June," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Emphasizing the need to combat terrorists, international
criminals and drug traffickers, Clinton also urged Congress,
saying "join me in pursuing an ambitions agenda to reduce the
serious threat of weapons of mass destruction."
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, he asked the Senate to ratify the comprehensive
nuclear test ban treaty.
</P>
<P>
"By ending nuclear testing, we can help to prevent the
development of new and more dangerous weapons and make it more
difficult for non-nuclear states to build them," he said.
</P>
<P>
The treaty was signed in September 1996 and 149 nations have
signed it as of January 1998, but only eight states have ratified
it. It will enter into force after 44 major countries including
the U.S. have ratified the treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
