<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Finance Minister Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Finance Minister Hiroshi
Mitsuzuka on Wednesday tendered his resignation to Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto as a token of responsibility for the arrests of
two top ministry banking inspectors on graft charges.
</P>
<P>
Mitsuzuka submitted a resignation letter at the prime
minister's official residence, the media reported.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto will handle the duties of finance minister until
Mitsuzuka's successor is named, government officials said.
</P>
<P>
Mitsuzuka's decision to resign came amidst tense political
confrontation between the ruling and opposition parties following
the arrest of two ministry inspectors suspected of having taken
bribes from banks in exchanges for tip-offs about ministry
inspections of those banks.
</P>
<P>
Diet (parliament) debates came to a halt Tuesday as opposition
parties demanded that Mitsuzuka step down.
</P>
<P>
After Mitsuzuka announced his resignation, opposition parties
agreed with the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) not to
boycott Diet deliberations on a supplementary budget for fiscal
1997 and other financial bills the government hopes will bolster
the economy.
</P>
<P>
Mitsuzuka had been in charge of the "Big Bang" liberalization
of Japan's financial sector, one of the six areas of reform
initiated by Hashimoto.
</P>
<P>
His resignation is widely viewed as a blow to Hashimoto, as the
prime minister has been struggling to stabilize the country's
financial system and stimulate the sluggish economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
