<HEADLINE> Meeting Discusses Impact of Asian Currency Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Some 40 participants from civil
society organizations in nine Asian countries gathered here on
Wednesday to discuss the impact of the current currency crisis on
employment, poverty and social integration.
</P>
<P>
The two-day event is a regional meeting of members of Social
Watch Asia, which is a part of Asia Watch, a global initiative of
non-governmental organizations monitoring the implementation of
social development programs in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Bangladesh, Cambodia, India, Indonesia, Japan,
Nepal, the Philippines, Sri Lanka and Thailand will be considered
during the meeting, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
The participants will also discuss ways to enhance networking
and exchange of information. The result of the meeting will be
reported to the United Nations Commission on Social Development in
February.
</P>
<P>
"We hear endless discussions on exchange rates and interest
rates. We hear the views of bankers and economists. It is time we
listen to the perspectives of civil society on how different
sectors of society are affected, especially the poor and the
marginalized," an organizer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
