<HEADLINE> French Hang-Glider Pilot Plunges to His Death in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 28 (Xinhua) -- A French hang-glider pilot
plunged to his death when his craft crashed during an
international competition in New South Wales state, police said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Gilles Le Borgne, 38, from Paris, was competing in the World
Flatlands Hang Gliding Championships at Forbes, in the state's
central west, when the accident happened late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A police spokeswoman said another contestant, from the
Netherlands, was forced to make an emergency landing after
swerving and missing the out-of-control Frenchman's glider.
</P>
<P>
The circumstances of the crash are unclear but the men were
flying at speeds in excess of 60 kilometers per hour, the
spokeswoman said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
