<HEADLINE> U.S. Identifies Potential Striking Targets on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The Pentagon on Tuesday
identified potential targets on Iraq once the Clinton
administration decides to strike against Iraq for its refusal of
abiding by U.N. resolutions on destroying weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
U.S. military planners have been looking for some time at
sites "of importance to (Iraqi President) Saddam (Hussein),"
Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Those sites, apart from suspected chemical and biological
weapons sites, would include his premier military units, the
Republican Guard, the special Republican Guard units that provide
security forces for his regime, and the units that gather
intelligence and send out commands to forces in the field, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Should Saddam decide to hit back with his suspected arsenal
of chemical and biological weapons, U.S. response would be
"decisive and devastating," Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether that might include the use of nuclear weapons,
Bacon said the United States has not "ruled anything in or out in
this matter."
</P>
<P>
All the potential military punishment on Iraq would be done
through air strikes, Bacon said. And attacks by ground troops
would not be encouraged, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
