<DOCNO> XIE19980128.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Accused of Seeking Continued Dominance in Panama </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The People's Party of
Panama accused the United States Tuesday of seeking to continue
its dominance of this Central American country into the 21st
century by establishing a multilateral anti-drug center.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the left wing People's Party said the
Multilateral Antidrug Center (CMA) is a violation of national
sovereignty and "a new model of the dominant U.S. geopolitical
stance towards Latin America cloaked as a multinational fight
against drug trafficking."
</P>
<P>
It said the CMA will be a replacement of the old Southern
Command -- the U.S. army for Latin America -- which has been
transferred from Panama to Miami.
</P>
<P>
The Southern Command was withdrawn in compliance with the
Torrijos-Carter treaties signed in 1977. These also mandated the
return of the Panama Canal and other U.S. facilities to Panama by
December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The left-wing party statement said that the objective of the
CMA is to be a multinational, political-military presence in
Panama, but it is actually one in which the U.S. is the
predominating force.
</P>
<P>
"In reality, mankind's interest in fighting the drug scourge,
which we also support, is being deceptively used by the U.S.,
utilizing this center to continue to occupy Panamanian territory
for purposes of dominance."
</P>
<P>
The party stated that the negotiations for the CMA have
designed a political-military complex in the context of the latest
U.S. geopolitical and national security doctrines to maintain
American supremacy into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Panama and the United States reached an agreement late last
year on the principle of establishing the CMA from the year 2000
on the Americans' Howard Air Force Base located in the Pacific
section of the Panama Canal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
