<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetans Celebrate Lunar New Year In Spite Of Blizzards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAINGOIN, TIBET, January 28 (Xinhua) -- When night fell on the
eve of the Chinese lunar new year, Baingoin, a normally quiet
county that occupies an isolated bit of grassland in northern
Tibet, became unusually noisy and excited.
</P>
<P>
And, although a succession of forty snowstorms since last
September have turned the grassland into a land of thick snow and ice,
relief materials from all over the country have been sent to help
the people celebrate the holiday.
</P>
<P>
Last night the people of Baingoin set off firecrackers, as if
to disperse the gloom caused by the persistent snowstorms.
</P>
<P>
Dundrub, a herdsman there, went to the gate of the county
government building to set off fireworks, and said that without
the government, he and the other herdsmen could not have gotten
through the disaster.
</P>
<P>
Liu Muyao, deputy-head of the county, and other local officials
called on several people last night who have been affected by the
storms, instead of having dinner with their own families in the
traditional way.
</P>
<P>
"This is the New Year's eve for the herdsmen of northern Tibet,
and I just can't be comfortable while these people live in need,"
he explained.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
