<HEADLINE> Chinese Keen on Touring Abroad During Spring Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 28 (Xinhua) -- More and more better-off
Chinese tend to spend the traditional Spring Festival, or Chinese
Lunar New Year, by touring overseas.
</P>
<P>
Residents in Guangzhou, capital of south China's booming
Guangdong Province, is a typical example.
</P>
<P>
Today, the first day of the festival's holidays, a 60-member
group, organized by the Guangdong International Tourism Agency, is
leaving for Australia and New Zealand on a visit. And tomorrow,
another 10-odd groups of holiday makers will fly to Singapore,
Malaysia and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 100,000 people of the city will go
elsewhere for the festival, 40 percent of whom plan to go abroad,
with the United States, Australia, and Southeast Asia being their
major destinations.
</P>
<P>
The city's urbanites prefer to tour Thailand this year, as the
charge of a five-day visit there has been cut from more than 4,000
Hong Kong dollars last year to some 2,800 now.
</P>
<P>
As a result, all flights to Thailand are full. So, China
Southern Airlines has arranged an extra flight on Thursday. And
its only air route to the United States and Australia that was
opened last year has also reported a marked rise of passengers.
</P>
<P>
The Airlines has put 30 planes into operation, including eight
Boeing-777s and 10 Airbus-320s, sources said. enditem
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
