<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Seeks IMF Program Extension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 28 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Central Bank Governor
Gabriel Singson has formally asked the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) to extend until the end of March the coverage of the
Extended Fund Facility program (EFF) to allow lawmakers to pass
the oil deregulation program.
</P>
<P>
According to the Manila Bulletin, Singson Tuesday sent a letter
to the IMF, formalizing the country's intention to ask for more
time to complete its commitments made under the EFF program.
</P>
<P>
Singson said the extension period was enough for the congress
to enact an oil industry deregulation law -- one of the
prerequisites for exiting from IMF's tutelage. The IMF requires
immediate full deregulation.
</P>
<P>
The new oil deregulation law was already approved by both
chambers of the congress. It is now with the bicameral conference
committee which is reconciling conflicting provisions in the
versions approved by the senate and the lower house.
</P>
<P>
The EFF program was started in July 1994 and was supposed to
expire last June. It was extended to December 31, 1997 because
another policy requirement, the comprehensive tax reform program,
was not yet approved by the congress at that time.
</P>
<P>
Singson said that even if the bicameral conference committee
approves the new oil deregulation law soon, the IMF would need
time to prepare the papers for the EFF executive board.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines is likely to get 345 million U.S. dollars in
financial assistance from the IMF if the executive board decides
that the country has substantially complied with the terms of the
EFF program.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
