<HEADLINE> Two Arrested for Forgery of Official Documents in Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, January 27 (Xinhua) -- A Costa Rican and a Cuban were
arrested in Costa Rica for allegedly forging the signature of the
Minister of Public Security to issue visas to Cubans who want to
leave their country, authorities said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Prosecutor Carlos Arias said that 12 false signatures of
Minister Laura Chichilla had been detected and that 25 others were
being investigated.
</P>
<P>
The arrested Costa Rican citizen was only identified by the
last name of Alfaro, while the police did not release any name for
the Cuban.
</P>
<P>
Other people may possibly be involved, including an immigration
official, Arias said.
</P>
<P>
Nearly two weeks ago, the Minister of Public Security, Laura
Chicilla, had reported the increased number of Cubans entering the
country, through suspicious marriages with Costa Rican citizens or
on the pretext of family reunions.
</P>
<P>
Investigations revealed the existence of an institution called
the National Committee of Churches that obtained visas for Cubans
for a fee of $7,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The arrested men forged the signature of the Minister on the
documents sent to the immigration authorities that authorized
issuing visas to citizens of Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica has no diplomatic or consular relations with Cuba
but has opened a special office in Havana. Moreover, an important
Cuban community lives in this Central American nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
