<HEADLINE> Britain Outlines Targets for Asia-Europe Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 27 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Office minister
Derek Fatchett said here Tuesday that the Second Asia-Europe
Summit (ASEM II) will be a "landmark" in the development of
Europe's relationship with Asia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a Foreign Office briefing here Tuesday morning,
Fatchett said that the ASEM II, due to take place in London on
April 3-4, will not be just another international meeting. "It
will be the focus for a diverse range of activities between Asia
and Europe, all with the common objective of building relations
and setting up cooperation between our two regions."
</P>
<P>
The British minister made it clear that the turmoil in Asian
financial markets will be high on the agenda of the summit
meeting. "We have a common interest in finding solutions and
restoring market confidence," he said.
</P>
<P>
Economic and trade cooperation will be another important target
of the Asian and Europe meeting. The British government is
expected to host a "Business Forum" to explore further business
opportunities between the two regions.
</P>
<P>
"The Business Forum will bring together top businessmen from
both regions so they can talk directly to their political
leaders," Fatchett said, adding, "the practical concerns of
business will be at the hearts of the ASEM discussions."
</P>
<P>
On the first ever China-European Union (EU) Summit to be held
during the ASEM II in London, Fatchett told Xinhua that Britain
was pleased that the summit will take place during Britain's EU
Presidency.
</P>
<P>
"We see that as a significant achievement for our (EU)
presidency. The (China-EU) summit is a substantial innovation and
contribution to the relations between EU and China," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We have a full agenda in terms of political engagements
between EU and China ranging from political global issues through
the agenda of human rights to our economic relationship," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
