<HEADLINE> U.S. Wages and Benefits Up 3.3 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, January 27 (Xinhua) -- The wages and benefits of
the U.S. workers increased 3.3 percent in 1997, the fastest growth
in four years, the Labor Department reported here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that the increase for the whole year was a
significant acceleration from a 2.9 percent rise for 1996 and a
2.7 percent increase in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The annual gain of 3.3 percent marked the fastest increase
since a 3.5 percent rise in 1993.
</P>
<P>
While rising wages and benefits are good news for workers,
economists worry that if those gains are not accompanied by
productivity increases, then inflation pressures can mount
quickly, often spelling an end to an economic expansion.
</P>
<P>
The 1 percent October to December gain in compensation costs
was slightly higher than the 0.9 percent analysts had been
expecting.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan has warned the
looming danger of wage inflation as one of the primary factors
that would prompt the Federal Reserve to begin raising interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
The jobless rate currently stands at the lowest levels in a
quarter of a century, standing at 4.7 percent in December. Despite
this fact, wage pressures have been restrained.
</P>
<P>
One of the major factors that has helped to restrain overall
compensation costs has recorded a marked slowdown in health
insurance. For 1997, health insurance and other benefits were up
2.1 percent, only slightly higher than a 2 percent growth in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Wages and salaries last year rose 3.8 percent, compared to a
gain of 3.3 percent in 1996. It was the fastest wage increase
since a 4.3 percent gain in 1990, at the end of the last long
recovery period.
</P>
<P>
For the final quarter, wages were up 1 percent, the fastest
quarterly pace since June 1990. Benefit costs climbed 0.9 percent,
also the fastest quarterly increase since a similar 0.9 percent
rise in the third quarter of 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
