<HEADLINE> Blair Hold Talks with N. Irish Parties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 27 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair held talks with the Northern Ireland parties on Tuesday in a
bid to defuse the crisis threatening peace talks.
</P>
<P>
He met leaders of all seven parties taking part in a peace
talks being held in Lancaster House in London after Protestant
leaders angrily rejected a new discussion paper.
</P>
<P>
"I made it clear that what is important is that the future of
Northern Ireland and a lasting political settlement can only be
put through if those people from the traditions of Northern
Ireland can come together and negotiate," Blair told reporters
emerging from his informal talks with the parties' leaders.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that it can be done provided people realise
that the details of any settlement have got to be negotiated,"
Blair said.
</P>
<P>
He also praised the publication of proposals for north-south
institutions by the UK and Irish governments.
</P>
<P>
The proposals aimed at driving the talks forward drew vastly
different reactions from Catholic and Protestant leaders when they
were published earlier on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The new proposals suggested a new Northern Ireland assembly,
closer London-Dublin links and powerful cross-border bodies to
foster Ireland-wide cooperation in trade and other sectors.
</P>
<P>
Catholic nationalist groups applauded the initiative, but the
Protestants were against it with scorn. The parties will continue
to discuss the initiative as well as the future of Northern
Ireland in London on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
