<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Commemorates Holocaust Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, January 27 (Xinhua) -- Commemorative events were held
across Germany Tuesday to pay respect to six million victims of
the Holocaust committed by German Nazis during World War II.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a special session of the German parliament Tuesday,
parliament speaker Rita Suessmuth called on Germans not to forget
the terrors committed by German Nazis.
</P>
<P>
"The courage to face the history enables a people to guard
against national madness and complacency," Suessmuth told the
parliament session with all German leaders present.
</P>
<P>
Also addressing the German parliament, Israeli historian Yehuda
Bauer warned against the danger of a repeated Holocaust and called
on the German people to make sure that a more humane and better
civilization has been developing from the debris of the history.
</P>
<P>
In the western German state of Rhineland-Palatinate, the state
parliament convened a special session in commemoration of Nazi
victims at a former Nazi concentration camp near the city of
Worms.
</P>
<P>
In the northern states of Schleswig-Holstein and Hamburg, local
authorities had ordered all public buildings to fly a flag at
half-mast. And in the former Dachau concentration camp near
Munich, more than 800 school children participated in a memorial
event alongside survivors of the camp.
</P>
<P>
In Berlin, where about 56,000 Jews were deported and murdered
by Nazis between 1941 and 1945, a memorial was unveiled Tuesday
before a railway station to mark the Jewish deportees.
</P>
<P>
January 27 was the day when Nazi victims in Auschwitz
concentration camp in Poland were liberalized by the Soviet troops
in 1945. The day was decided by German President Roman Herzog as a
rememberance day in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
